14-02-15 19:57:10','2014-02-15 19:57:10','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(411,1,'2014-03-14 01:41:40','2014-03-14 01:41:40','','ready_to_learn_1000x400','','inherit','open','open','','ready_to_learn_1000x400','','','2014-03-14 01:41:40','2014-03-14 01:41:40','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/ready_to_learn_1000x400.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(123,1,'2014-02-16 17:16:14','2014-02-16 17:16:14','Send us an e-mail:\r\n\r\n[bestwebsoft_contact_form]','Contact Us','','publish','open','closed','','contact','','','2014-03-19 02:16:38','2014-03-19 02:16:38','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=123',6,'page','',0),(490,1,'2014-03-19 02:16:38','2014-03-19 02:16:38','Send us an e-mail:\r\n\r\n[bestwebsoft_contact_form]','Contact Us','','inherit','open','open','','123-revision-v1','','','2014-03-19 02:16:38','2014-03-19 02:16:38','',123,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/123-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(124,1,'2014-02-16 17:16:14','2014-02-16 17:16:14','','Contact','','inherit','open','open','','123-revision-v1','','','2014-02-16 17:16:14','2014-02-16 17:16:14','',123,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?p=124',0,'revision','',0),(126,1,'2014-02-16 17:20:11','2014-02-16 17:20:11','[bestwebsoft_contact_form]','Contact','','inherit','open','open','','123-revision-v1','','','2014-02-16 17:20:11','2014-02-16 17:20:11','',123,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?p=126',0,'revision','',0),(127,1,'2014-02-16 17:25:50','2014-02-16 17:25:50','<strong>This is the home page!</strong>\r\n\r\nLorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Curabitur nec semper sapien, eget varius ante. Quisque eleifend id turpis ut tempor. Fusce in velit nulla. Cum sociis natoque penatibus et magnis dis parturient montes, nascetur ridiculus mus. In nec mauris fringilla, sodales enim sed, auctor ligula. Ut pretium neque euismod mi imperdiet pharetra. Nulla arcu erat, consectetur quis ornare in, varius nec turpis. Praesent ligula nulla, placerat eleifend tincidunt id, vulputate in nunc. Curabitur id risus vehicula, varius eros sed, tempor mauris. Nunc luctus faucibus justo a eleifend. Maecenas sit amet turpis semper, molestie libero eget, egestas urna. Pellentesque quis luctus urna. Mauris elementum elit at congue viverra. Aenean tempus ipsum non arcu tincidunt consectetur.\r\n\r\n[donate count=2 type=default]','Home','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2014-02-16 17:25:50','2014-02-16 17:25:50','',13,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?p=127',0,'revision','',0),(174,1,'2014-02-26 05:08:11','2014-02-26 05:08:11','The HMBT order has relied entirely on receiving outside donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from any parent organization.   The HMBT is registered as an Indian NGO under the secular name Sneha Jewan Kendra which means Love and Life Center.\r\n\r\nOn this page you can see a list of the major current needs at the orphanages.  Your contribution is greatly appreciated.','Give','','inherit','open','open','','11-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 05:08:11','2014-02-26 05:08:11','',11,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/11-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(140,1,'2014-02-26 01:38:02','2014-02-26 01:38:02','<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages are a place for slum and underprivileged children to grow up and get an education.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There are currently two main locations in greater Mumbai, India:  Sahar (Church Pakdi) Slum  and  Merces-Giriz</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They have been in existence for more than 20 years</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They are run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They developed as a result of the HMBT outreach work in the slums of Mumbai</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n[donate count=2 type=default]','Home','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:38:02','2014-02-26 01:38:02','',13,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/13-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(131,1,'2014-02-26 01:20:21','2014-02-26 01:20:21','<p dir=\"ltr\">Sr. Paulette comes from a Christian Indian family from the island of Mauritus.  In her youth she decided to become a nun and came to Calcutta to join Mother Teresa.  For about 20 years she worked with Mother Teresa mainly helping women and children and doing family planning work.  She developed a severe back condition which required hospitalization. She was sent to a Mumbai hospital where she spent several months.  When she emerged from recuperation Mother Teresa urged her to remain in Mumbai in a life of service.  This is how, in 1989,  she became the foundress of a new order of nuns called the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.  Today the order contains about 40 nuns;  about 10 of these are directly working with Sr. Paulette at the orphanages.</p>\r\n&nbsp;','Paulette','','inherit','open','open','','25-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:20:21','2014-02-26 01:20:21','',25,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/25-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(132,1,'2014-02-26 01:21:42','2014-02-26 01:21:42','<p dir=\"ltr\">Sister Eliza comes from a Christian Indian family in Goa.  She came to Mumbai to study Social Work.  She completed college and a M.A. degree in Social Work.  She was very much drawn to helping the abandoned and poor.  During this time, around 1990,  she was introduced to Sr. Paulette and became the first Sister to join the HMBT.  For more than 20 years now she has been a strong pillar to the order.  Today she spends most of her time running the day to day affairs of the Sahar Orphanage.  She also teaches at a nearby school and through this employment brings in financial support to run the orphanage.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/nuns.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-22\" alt=\"nuns\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/nuns-225x300.png\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>','Eliza','','inherit','open','open','','23-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:21:42','2014-02-26 01:21:42','',23,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/23-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(651,1,'2014-03-28 13:36:46','2014-03-28 13:36:46','<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Sahar Slum Orphanage &amp; School</strong></span>:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity Orphanage, Rd. No. 2, Church Pakadi,  Sahar Village, Andheri  East,  Mumbai - 99   India</p>\r\n[googlemap height=\"300\" zoom=\"12\" lat=\"19.1017135,72.8681533\"][marker lat=\"19.1017135,72.8681533\" title=\"Sahar Orphanage\"][/googlemap]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Merces &amp; Giriz Orphanages</strong></span>:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity Orphanage,  Sapodi Wadi,  Kawlar Budruk,  Mari Naka,  Merces,  Vasai,</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">District Thane -  401 201,   Mumbai,    India</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&amp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity Orphanage,  Chauri Wadi,  Giriz Talaw,  Giriz,  District Thane - 401 201,  Mumbai,  India</p>\r\n[googlemap height=\"300\" zoom=\"12\" lat=\"19.3599382\" long=\"72.7892803\"][marker lat=\"19.3599382\" long=\"72.7892803\" title=\"Merces Orphanage\"][marker lat=\"19.3715985\" long=\"72.7951597\" title=\"Giriz Orphanage\"][/googlemap]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Postal Addresses','','inherit','open','open','','481-revision-v1','','','2014-03-28 13:36:46','2014-03-28 13:36:46','',481,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/481-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(137,1,'2014-02-26 01:28:58','2014-02-26 01:28:58','<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01143-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-697\" alt=\"DSC01143 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01143-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"427\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Amma is the resident caretaker of the orphans at Sahar.  She is in her 70’s, a widow.  She was shunned by her own family. This is how she came to  join the family of the HBT nuns and orphans for whom she has worked tirelessly for the past 15 years.  She is responsible for cooking, feeding, bathing and dressing the kids,  and being a grandmother to all of them.</p>','Amma','','publish','open','closed','','amma','','','2014-04-11 12:56:13','2014-04-11 12:56:13','',7,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=137',2,'page','',0),(138,1,'2014-02-26 01:28:58','2014-02-26 01:28:58','','Amma','','inherit','open','open','','137-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:28:58','2014-02-26 01:28:58','',137,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/137-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(139,1,'2014-02-26 01:30:49','2014-02-26 01:30:49','<p dir=\"ltr\">Amma is the resident caretaker of the orphans at Sahar.  She is in her 70’s, a widow.  She was shunned by her own family and so has joined the family of the HMBT nuns and orphans for whom she has worked tirelessly for the past 15 years.  She is responsible for cooking, feeding, bathing and dressing the kids and being a grandmother to all of them.</p>','Amma','','inherit','open','open','','137-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:30:49','2014-02-26 01:30:49','',137,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/137-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(141,1,'2014-02-26 01:49:04','2014-02-26 01:49:04','<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The Handmaids Orphanages and School were started by nuns (sisters) of an order known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HBT). </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The missionary work of the HBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, and up to recently,  there were only two nuns in the order,   Sr. Paulette and Sr. Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas bordering the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums.</span></p>\r\nLiving and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: not having enough food leading to severe malnutrition,\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7610-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-451\" alt=\"DSCF7610 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7610-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nliving in ramshackle huts without electricity or a bathroom,\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7590-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-455\" alt=\"DSCF7590 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7590-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nand children not going to school.   In the huts and in the streets they did counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance. Through their outreach the Sisters became known in the area and to local social service agencies.  Often,  orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually they realized it was necessary for them to start  their own orphanage.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Sr.-Paulette-with-kids1.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-755\" alt=\"Sr. Paulette with kids\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Sr.-Paulette-with-kids1.jpg\" width=\"359\" height=\"465\" /></a>\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum the Sisters were taking care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager slum hut.  Upon her death her property, which had been willed to the local church, was purchased by the Sisters.  This became their home base,  their convent house in the slum.    Around that same time they received a donation of land in a suburb of Mumbai called Merces &amp; Giriz  on which they were able to build a larger convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces - Giriz sites were eventually developed to become orphanages and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.\r\n\r\nThe HBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Sisters were helped greatly by charitable donations from the Mumbai division of  J.P. Morgan Bank.  They were able to use this large assistance to do much needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF6974-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-459\" alt=\"DSCF6974 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF6974-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nOver the years,  the order of nuns of the HBT has grown from just 2 nuns to recently about 40 nuns.  About 10 of these are involved with the orphanages in the Mumbai area and the remainder are doing parish work in other parts of India.\r\n\r\nThe sisters have had to overcome many challenges in being responsible for all the orphans under their care.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01017-resized.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-659\" alt=\"DSC01017 resized\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01017-resized.jpg\" width=\"490\" height=\"368\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThen, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night after attending to their missionary work diligently.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01016-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-605\" alt=\"DSC01016 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01016-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any male residential mentors or father figures.  Also,  it was not possible to maintain separate living quarters for boys and girls.\r\n\r\nThere is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claim them. Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is needed and maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They have worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage House which doubles as classroom spaces.   Over the years this school has become more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent slums.  Today, 300 students representing multiple grade levels up to 7th standard attend this school,  all crammed in a space not more than 2000 square feet.  When the school day is over the space reverts to being the living quarters for the 30  resident orphans and their caretakers.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7229-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-461\" alt=\"DSCF7229 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7229-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees ($ 7)  per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable to their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the Sahar slum kids would receive no education.\r\n\r\nAt the Merces - Giriz orphanages the girls attend  schools in the local community.  They all take a bus or walk to get to school.   Their school fees are borne by the HMBT along with any contribution given by family members of the orphans.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-617\" alt=\"DSC01053 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>','History','','publish','open','closed','','history','','','2014-04-11 13:01:13','2014-04-11 13:01:13','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=141',1,'page','',0),(142,1,'2014-02-26 01:49:04','2014-02-26 01:49:04','<p dir=\"ltr\">The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is called Church Pakadi).</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to social service agencies.  Often orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses but grew to become orphanages, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Over the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now,  the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For practical reasons they have evolved gradually into their current set up in which they only have girls under their care.  The boys they previously had have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  There is also some turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school for slum children at Sahar.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  The children attending this school have no other viable option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable.  The HMBT school offers a low cost English medium education in subjects ranging from science, to math, to crafts, to language.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT</p>','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:49:04','2014-02-26 01:49:04','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(143,1,'2014-02-26 01:54:03','2014-02-26 01:54:03','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of n