very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses but grew to become orphanages, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 to now about 40 nuns (about 10 of these involved with the orphanages).\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually, for practical reasons,  into their current set up in which they are  girls only orphanages.  The boys  previously residing there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage.   Over the years the school became more widely attended by even the non-orphan children from the adjacent and nearby slums.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  A typical classroom is about 200 square feet and holds about 30 kids.  The teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable.  The HMBT school offers a low cost English medium education in subjects ranging from science, to math, to crafts, to language.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 14:23:17','2014-02-26 14:23:17','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(196,1,'2014-03-31 18:42:40','2014-03-31 18:42:40','<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01037-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-689\" alt=\"DSC01037 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01037-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Ruby was born in June 1999.   Both of her parents passed away of unknown causes.  She was living with her sister but upon her sister\'s marriage she was brought to the Merces Orphanage about a year ago.</p>\nRuby\'s favorite subjects in school are Speech (in which she enters competitions) and Singing (for which she has won awards).  She hopes someday to be a doctor because it is \"a respectable career\".   She really values all the people caring for her at the orphanage and feels a sense of community.  She said she would rather stay at the orphanage than to go back to her previous life.','Ruby Kureshi','','inherit','open','open','','156-autosave-v1','','','2014-03-31 18:42:40','2014-03-31 18:42:40','',156,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/156-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(197,1,'2014-02-26 14:27:55','2014-02-26 14:27:55','Ruby was born in June 1999.   Both of her parents passed away of unknown causes.  She was living with her sister but upon her sister\'s marriage she was brought to the Merces Orphanage about a year ago.\r\n\r\nRuby\'s favorite subjects in school are Speech (in which she enters competitions) and Singing (for which she has won awards).  She hopes someday to be a doctor because it is \"a respectable career\".   She really values all the people caring for her at the orphanage and feels a sense of community.  She said she would rather stay at the orphanage than to go back to her previous life.','Ruby Kureshi','','inherit','open','open','','156-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 14:27:55','2014-02-26 14:27:55','',156,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/156-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(198,1,'2014-03-12 13:22:34','2014-03-12 13:22:34','<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01040-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-255\" alt=\"DSC01040 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01040-Small.jpg\" width=\"480\" height=\"640\" /></a>Supriya is currently in 6th standard and has lived at the Merces Orphanage since 2007.   When both her parents died of tuberculosis she was brought to the orphanage by her grandmother who  had to go to work and had no means to support her.   She is expected to return to her grandmother after 10th grade but she is not sure she wants to go back.   She has one brother who is 14 years old who lives in another orphanage and visits on Sundays.\n\nSupriya attends St. Anthony\'s Convent School where she is average in her class of 80 kids.  She hopes to be an aritist someday.','Supriya Naka','','inherit','open','open','','158-autosave-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:22:34','2014-03-12 13:22:34','',158,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/158-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(199,1,'2014-02-26 14:36:19','2014-02-26 14:36:19','Supriya is currently in 6th standard and has lived at the Merces Orphanage since 2007.   When both her parents died of tuberculosis she was brought to the orphanage by her grandmother who  had to go to work and had no means to support her.   She is expected to return to her grandmother after 10th grade but she is not sure she wants to go back.   She has one brother who is 14 years old who lives in another orphanage and visits on Sundays.\r\n\r\nSupriya attends St. Anthony\'s Convent School where she is average in her class of 80 kids.  She hopes to be an aritist someday.','Supriya Naka','','inherit','open','open','','158-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 14:36:19','2014-02-26 14:36:19','',158,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/158-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(200,1,'2014-02-26 14:38:46','2014-02-26 14:38:46','Arti was born in September 1998.  Her father divorced her mother and ran away.  Her mother works as a live in maid in someone\'s house and is unable to have Arti with her but visits her on Sundays.\n\nShe is currently in the 8th standard and has lived at Merces Orphanage since 2009.  She hopes someday to become a police officer because she wants to enforce ju','Arti Gaikwade','','inherit','open','open','','160-autosave-v1','','','2014-02-26 14:38:46','2014-02-26 14:38:46','',160,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/160-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(201,1,'2014-02-26 14:39:30','2014-02-26 14:39:30','Arti was born in September 1998.  Her father divorced her mother and ran away.  Her mother works as a live-in-maid in someone\'s house and is unable to have Arti with her but visits her on Sundays.\r\n\r\nShe is currently in the 8th standard and has lived at Merces Orphanage since 2009.  She hopes someday to become a police officer because she \"wants to enforce justice\".','Arti Gaikwade','','inherit','open','open','','160-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 14:39:30','2014-02-26 14:39:30','',160,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/160-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(202,1,'2014-02-26 14:44:00','2014-02-26 14:44:00','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is called Church Pakadi).</p>\r\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to social service agencies.  Often orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses but grew to become orphanages, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 to now about 40 nuns (about 10 of these involved with the orphanages).\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any residential mentors or father figures.  Also it was not possible to have separate living quarters.    There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage.   Over the years the school became more widely attended by even the non-orphan children from the adjacent and nearby slums.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  A typical classroom is about 200 square feet and holds about 30 kids.  The teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable.  The HMBT school offers a low cost English medium education in subjects ranging from science, to math, to crafts, to language.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 14:44:00','2014-02-26 14:44:00','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(203,1,'2014-04-01 17:47:17','2014-04-01 17:47:17','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">\n</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">                  <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Custom.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-705\" alt=\"DSC01134 (Custom)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Custom.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>                 <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Custom.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-375\" alt=\"DSC01136 (Custom)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Custom.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"240\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">                                          Tulsi                                                                             Gauri</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tulsi was born November 2003 and her sister Gauri was born April 2005.  Both are living at the Sahar Orphanage.  They are in 3rd and 2nd standard respectively.  Their mother died in a road accident.  Their father had no job and was homeless so he brought the girls to the orphanage.   He hopes to collect them after they complete school through the 7th standard at Sahar,  by which time he hopes his personal situation will have improved.</p>','Tulsi & Gauri Shetty','','inherit','open','open','','162-autosave-v1','','','2014-04-01 17:47:17','2014-04-01 17:47:17','',162,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/162-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(204,1,'2014-02-26 14:49:15','2014-02-26 14:49:15','Tulsi was born November 2003 and her sister Gauri was born April 2005.  Both are living at the Sahar Orphanage.  They are in 3rd and 2nd standard respectively.  Their mother died in a road accident.  Their father had no job and was homeless so he brought the girls to the orphanage.   He hopes to collect them after they complete school through the 7th standard at Sahar,  by which time he hopes his personal situation will have improved.','Tulsi & Gauri Shetty','','inherit','open','open','','162-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 14:49:15','2014-02-26 14:49:15','',162,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/162-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(205,1,'2014-02-26 14:56:41','2014-02-26 14:56:41','Sneha was born September 2003.   She is currently healthy.  She has been living at the Sahar Orphanage since the age of 3 when she was brought there by her grandmother who still visits.\n\nHer father had burned her mother to death over a property dispute and spent some time in jail.  His brother bought for him his way out of jail within the corrupt system in India.  He is forbidden from seeing Sneha.  Her brother Sopnil is 2 years older.  He was living at the Merces Orphange but is currently at another orphanage.\n\nShe attends 3rd standard at the Sahar Orphanage School and is maintaining an average academic performance in her class of 50 students.','Sneha Borde','','inherit','open','open','','164-autosave-v1','','','2014-02-26 14:56:41','2014-02-26 14:56:41','',164,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/164-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(206,1,'2014-02-26 14:58:20','2014-02-26 14:58:20','Sneha was born September 2003.   She is currently healthy.  She has been living at the Sahar Orphanage since the age of 3 when she was brought there by her grandmother who still visits.\r\n\r\nHer father had burned her mother to death over a property dispute and spent some time in jail.  His brother bought for him his way out of jail within the corrupt system in India.  He is forbidden from seeing Sneha.  Her brother Sopnil is 2 years older.  He was living at the Merces Orphange but is currently at another orphanage.\r\n\r\nShe attends 3rd standard at the Sahar Orphanage School and is maintaining an average academic performance in her class of 50 students.','Sneha Borde','','inherit','open','open','','164-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 14:58:20','2014-02-26 14:58:20','',164,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/164-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(207,1,'2014-02-26 15:01:18','2014-02-26 15:01:18','There are about 30 orphans at Sahar and about 100 at Merces-Giriz.  They range from 3 years to 16 years old.  Their parents have died either due to disease or violent crime or self neglect or are in prison.\r\n\r\nSome of the kids are not \"orphans\" but have been brought by a parent or family member because they are physically or financially unable to care for them.  Often, there will be one surviving parent or a distant relative that continues to visit their child at the orphanages and this individual will eventually accept the child back.   But while they are there, the HMBT Sisters care for them completely.\r\n\r\nOn a typical day they will arise at 5:30-6:00 am.  After eating breakfast they will get dressed and ready for school which  goes till the early afternoon.   At Sahar the school is in the same building;  at Merces-Giriz the kids take a bus or walk to nearby independent schools.   In the mid-afternoon there is additonal tutoring by a paid teacher at Sahar and by volunteer local college students at Merces-Giriz .  In the late afternoon the kids all do chores, have play time,  take baths, eat dinner and have prayer time.  They typically go to bed around 9 pm.    On Sundays, there is extra time for watching T.V.,  having a party, music, dance,  and also visits by family members or persons from the community.\r\n\r\nOn this page you will find some profiles typical of the orphans.','Orphans','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 15:01:18','2014-02-26 15:01:18','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/151-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(208,1,'2014-02-26 15:09:19','2014-02-26 15:09:19','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989 up until recently,  it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is in the Church Pakadi slum).</p>\r\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to social service agencies.  Often orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses for the HMBT order but grew to become orphanages around 1996, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 nuns to recently about 40 nuns.  About 10 of these are involved with the orphanages and the remainder are doing parish work in other states in India.\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any residential mentors or father figures.  Also it was not possible to maintain separate living quarters for boys and girls.    There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage.   Over the years the school became more widely attended by even the non-orphan children from the adjacent and nearby slums.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  A typical classroom is about 200 square feet and holds about 30 kids.  The teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable.  The HMBT school offers a low cost English medium education in subjects ranging from science, to math, to crafts, to language.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 15:09:19','2014-02-26 15:09:19','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(209,1,'2014-04-04 14:12:39','2014-04-04 14:12:39','*  The main orphanage house at Merces has a leaking roof over the room in which 100 orphans store their school bags and books.   A covered terrace needs to be constructed above this room.  This terrace will also functions as a space to hang up all the laundry to dry.  Currently the clothes are washed by hand as part of the chores of the orphans.   There is no covered place to hang laundry for drying - so there is no way to dry clothes when it rains, especially in the monsoon season.    The estimated cost for this project is: _________\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01193-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSC01193 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01193-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\n&nbsp;\n\n* The electrical wiring in the main orphanage house at Merces needs to be replaced.  Currently there are exposed wires and some of the wires are in disrepair.   The estimated cost for this project is:_________\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01195-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-748\" alt=\"DSC01195 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01195-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Current Needs','','inherit','open','open','','169-autosave-v1','','','2014-04-04 14:12:39','2014-04-04 14:12:39','',169,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/169-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(210,1,'2014-03-01 17:27:29','2014-03-01 17:27:29','*  The main orphanage house at Merces has a leaking roof over the room in which  the kids have shelves to put their school bags and books.  The sisters would like to remedy this by constructing a covered terrace above this room which will also give a space to hang up all the laundry to dry.  Currently the clothes are washed by hand as part of the chores of the orphans.   There is no covered place to hang laundry for drying - so there is no way to dry clothes when it rains.    The estimated cost for this project is: _________\r\n\r\nXXXX ATTACH PICTURES OF THE LEAKING ROOF XXXX\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n* The electrical wiring in the main orphanage house at Merces needs to be replaced.  Currently there are exposed wires and the wires are in dis-repair.   The estimated cost for this project is:_________\r\n\r\nXXXXX  ATTACH PICTURES OF EXPOSED WIRING XXXXX\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Current Needs','','inherit','open','open','','169-revision-v1','','','2014-03-01 17:27:29','2014-03-01 17:27:29','',169,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/169-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(212,1,'2014-03-10 00:38:30','2014-03-10 00:38:30','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, and up to recently,  it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is in the Church Pakadi slum).</p>\r\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to local social service agencies.  Often,  orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses for the HMBT order but grew to become orphanages around 1996, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 nuns to recently about 40 nuns.  About 10 of these are involved with the orphanages and the remainder are doing parish work in other states in India.\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any male residential mentors or father figures.  Also,  it was not possible to maintain separate living quarters for boys and girls.    There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage.   Over the years the school became more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent and nearby slums.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  A typical classroom is about 200 square feet and holds about 30 kids.  The teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-03-10 00:38:30','2014-03-10 00:38:30','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(213,1,'2014-03-10 00:43:19','2014-03-10 00:43:19','<p dir=\"ltr\">Sister Eliza comes from a Christian Indian family in Goa.  She came to Mumbai to study Social Work.  She completed college and a M.A. degree in Social Work.  She was very much drawn to helping the abandoned and poor.  During this time, around 1990,  she was introduced to Sr. Paulette and became the first Sister to join the HMBT.  For more than 20 years now she has been a strong pillar to the order.  Today she spends most of her time running the day to day affairs of the Sahar Orphanage.  She also teaches at a nearby private school,  and through this employment,  brings in financial support to run the orphanage.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/nuns.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-22\" alt=\"nuns\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/nuns-225x300.png\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>','Eliza','','inherit','open','open','','23-revision-v1','','','2014-03-10 00:43:19','2014-03-10 00:43:19','',23,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/23-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(214,1,'2014-04-01 17:34:52','2014-04-01 17:34:52','<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01143-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-697\" alt=\"DSC01143 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01143-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"427\" /></a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Amma is the resident caretaker of the orphans at Sahar.  She is in her 70’s, a widow.  She was shunned by her own family.  This is how she came to  join the family of the HMBT nuns and orphans for whom she has worked tirelessly for the past 15 years.  She is responsible for cooking, feeding, bathing and dressing the kids,  and being a grandmother to all of them.</p>','Amma','','inherit','open','open','','137-autosave-v1','','','2014-04-01 17:34:52','2014-04-01 17:34:52','',137,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/137-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(215,1,'2014-03-10 00:45:11','2014-03-10 00:45:11','<p dir=\"ltr\">Amma is the resident caretaker of the orphans at Sahar.  She is in her 70’s, a widow.  She was shunned by her own family.  This is how she came to  join the family of the HMBT nuns and orphans for whom she has worked tirelessly for the past 15 years.  She is responsible for cooking, feeding, bathing and dressing the kids,  and being a grandmother to all of them.</p>','Amma','','inherit','open','open','','137-revision-v1','','','2014-03-10 00:45:11','2014-03-10 00:45:11','',137,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/137-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(216,1,'2014-03-10 00:48:46','2014-03-10 00:48:46','There are about 30 orphans at Sahar and about 100 at Merces-Giriz.  They range from 3 years to 16 years old.  Their parents have died either due to disease, violent crime,  self neglect,  or are in prison.\r\n\r\nSome of the kids are not \"orphans\" but have been brought by a parent or family member because they are physically or financially unable to care for them.  Often, there will be one surviving parent or a distant relative that continues to visit their child at the orphanages and this individual will eventually accept the child back.   But while they are there, the HMBT Sisters care for them completely.\r\n\r\nOn a typical day they will arise at 5:30-6:00 am.  After eating breakfast they will get dressed and ready for school which  goes till the early afternoon.   At Sahar the school is within the orphanage house itself;  at Merces-Giriz the kids take a bus or walk to nearby independent schools.   In the mid-afternoon there is additonal tutoring by a paid teacher at Sahar and by volunteer local college students at Merces-Giriz.  In the late afternoon the kids all do homework,  chores, have play time,  take baths, eat dinner and have prayer time.  They typically go to bed around 9 pm.    On Sundays, there is extra time for watching T.V.,  having a party, music, dance,  and also visits by family members or persons from the community.\r\n\r\nOn this page you will find some profiles typical of the orphans.','Orphans','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-v1','','','2014-03-10 00:48:46','2014-03-10 00:48:46','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/151-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(217,1,'2014-03-10 00:55:54','2014-03-10 00:55:54','The HMBT order has relied entirely on receiving outside donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from any parent organization.   The HMBT is registered as an Indian NGO under the secular name Sneha Jewan Kendra which means Love and Life Center.  Effort is currently underway to register Sneha Jewan Kendra in the United States as a charitable 501 C 3 organization.\r\n\r\nOn this page you can see a list of the major current needs at the orphanages.  Your contribution is greatly appreciated.','Give','','inherit','open','open','','11-revision-v1','','','2014-03-10 00:55:54','2014-03-10 00:55:54','',11,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/11-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(219,1,'2014-03-10 01:02:22','2014-03-10 01:02:22','<p dir=\"ltr\">Sister Eliza comes from a Christian Indian family in Goa.  She came to Mumbai to study Social Work.  She completed college and a M.A. degree in Social Work.  She was very much drawn to helping the abandoned and poor.  During this time, around 1990,  she was introduced to Sr. Paulette and became the first Sister to join the HMBT.  For more than 20 years now she has been a strong pillar to the order.  Today she spends most of her time running the day to day affairs of the Sahar Orphanage.  She also teaches at a nearby private school,  and through this employment,  brings in financial support to run the orphanage.</p>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary13.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-85\" alt=\"diary13\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary13-225x300.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>','Eliza','','inherit','open','open','','23-revision-v1','','','2014-03-10 01:02:22','2014-03-10 01:02:22','',23,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/23-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(221,1,'2014-03-10 01:39:07','2014-03-10 01:39:07','This is a log of a visit to the HMBT orphanages in December, 2009 written by a 13 year old girl and her father.','Diary of a Visit','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision-v1','','','2014-03-10 01:39:07','2014-03-10 01:39:07','',9,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/9-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(222,1,'2014-03-10 16:36:12','2014-03-10 16:36:12','There are three main orphanage sites run by the HBT:   Sahar Slum Orhanage,  Merces Orphanage,  and Giriz Orphanage\r\n\r\n<strong>Sahar Slum Orphanage:</strong>\r\n\r\nThis ophanage is located in a Mumbai slum called Sahar Village and is adjacent to the International Airport in Mumbai (<a title=\"Postal Addresses\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/contact/postal-addresses\" target=\"_blank\">see location</a>).  There are 30 resident orphans living here and their care taker known as <a title=\"Amma\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/history/sister-bios/amma\">Amma</a>.    On most days Sisters of the HBT are also there.   The orphanage house is also used as a school that serves 300 children from the surrounding slums.  At the end of the school day the space reverts back to being an orphanage.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01160-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-593\" alt=\"DSC01160 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01160-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"427\" /></a>             <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7475-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSCF7475 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7475-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Merces Orphanage:</strong>\r\n\r\nThis is the largest orphanage.  It is located just north of the city of Mumbai near a suburb called Vasai (<a title=\"Postal Addresses\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/contact/postal-addresses#vasai\" target=\"_blank\">see location</a>).  Approximately 100 orphans live in this house which is only about 2000 square feet.  It is also the primary residential quarters of Srs. Paulette and Eliza and two other sisters.  It is a very busy and congested house but is kept well organized.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01034-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-599\" alt=\"DSC01034 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01034-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>      <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01022-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-600\" alt=\"DSC01022 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01022-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Giriz Orphanage:    </strong>\r\n\r\nThis orphanage is located about 2 Km. from the Merces Orphanage (<a title=\"Postal Addresses\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/contact/postal-addresses#vasai\" target=\"_blank\">see location</a>).   It is the newest building of the three,  and is currently used to house the older,  most independent girls under the supervision of the Handmaids.  Currently about 7-10 girls reside here.   Here they have a chance to focus on their school studies  in a more quiet environment.   Across the road from this orphanage is the Giriz Formation House of the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity Order.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01190-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-608\" alt=\"DSC01190 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01190-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Orphanages','','publish','open','open','','locations','','','2014-04-11 13:11:05','2014-04-11 13:11:05','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=222',2,'page','',0),(223,1,'2014-03-10 16:36:12','2014-03-10 16:36:12','Main locations page.','Locations','','inherit','open','open','','222-revision-v1','','','2014-03-10 16:36:12','2014-03-10 16:36:12','',222,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/222-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(225,1,'2014-03-11 00:33:39','2014-03-11 00:33:39','<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A safe and nurturing orphanage environment</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For slum and underprivileged children to grow up and get an education.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two main locations in Mumbai, India</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">Run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT) since 1989</li>\r\n</ul>','About','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2014-03-11 00:33:39','2014-03-11 00:33:39','',13,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/13-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(226,1,'2014-03-11 00:33:59','2014-03-11 00:33:59','<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A safe and nurturing orphanage environment</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For slum and underprivileged children to grow up and get an education.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two main locations in Mumbai, India</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">Run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT) since 1989</li>\r\n</ul>','Home','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2014-03-11 00:33:59','2014-03-11 00:33:59','',13,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/13-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(228,1,'2014-03-12 01:21:09','2014-03-12 01:21:09','','DSC01178 (Small)','','inherit','open','open','','dsc01178-small','','','2014-03-12 01:21:09','2014-03-12 01:21:09','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01178-Small.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(229,1,'2014-03-12 01:21:11','2014-03-12 01:21:11','','DSC01179 (Small)','','inherit','open','open','','dsc01179-small','','','2014-03-12 01:21:11','2014-03-12 01:21:11','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01179-Small.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(230,1,'2014-03-12 01:21:12','2014-03-12 01:21:12','','DSC01181 (Small)','','inherit','open','open','','dsc01181-small','','','2014-03-12 01:21:12','2014-03-12 01:21:12','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01181-Small.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(231,1,'2014-03-12 01:21:13','2014-03-12 01:21:13','','DSC01190 (Small)','','inherit','open','open','','dsc01190-small','','','2014-03-12 01:21:13','2014-03-12 01:21:13','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01190-Small.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(232,1,'2014-03-12 01: