4-03-13 00:54:58','','Sister Bios','','inherit','open','open','','7-revision-v1','','','2014-03-13 00:54:58','2014-03-13 00:54:58','',7,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/7-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(354,1,'2014-03-12 13:29:01','2014-03-12 13:29:01','<p dir=\"ltr\">Sister Eliza comes from a Christian Indian family in Goa.  She came to Mumbai to study Social Work.  She completed college and a M.A. degree in Social Work.  She was very much drawn to helping the abandoned and poor.  During this time, around 1990,  she was introduced to Sr. Paulette and became the first Sister to join the HMBT.  For more than 20 years now she has been a strong pillar to the order.  Today she spends most of her time running the day to day affairs of the Sahar Orphanage.  She also teaches at a nearby private school,  and through this employment,  brings in financial support to run the orphanage.</p>\r\n&nbsp;','Eliza','','inherit','open','open','','23-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:29:01','2014-03-12 13:29:01','',23,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/23-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(410,1,'2014-03-14 01:41:22','2014-03-14 01:41:22','<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The HMBT order has relied entirely on receiving outside donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from any parent organization.   The HMBT is registered as an Indian NGO under the secular name Sneha Jewan Kendra which means Love and Life Center.  Effort is currently underway to register Sneha Jewan Kendra in the United States as a charitable 501 C 3 organization.</span>\r\n\r\nOn this page you can see a list of the major current needs at the orphanages.  Your contribution is greatly appreciated.\r\n\r\n<form action=\"https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr\" method=\"post\" target=\"_blank\"><input type=\"hidden\" name=\"cmd\" value=\"_s-xclick\" />\r\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"hosted_button_id\" value=\"BGG3VL42SCA5L\" />\r\n<input type=\"image\" alt=\"PayPal - The safer, easier way to pay online!\" name=\"submit\" src=\"https://www.paypalobjects.com/en_US/i/btn/btn_donateCC_LG.gif\" />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://www.paypalobjects.com/en_US/i/scr/pixel.gif\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" border=\"0\" /></form>','Support Us','','inherit','open','open','','11-revision-v1','','','2014-03-14 01:41:22','2014-03-14 01:41:22','',11,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/11-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(341,1,'2014-03-12 12:03:05','2014-03-12 12:03:05','[pagetitle]About Us[/pagetitle]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A safe and nurturing orphanage environment</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For slum and underprivileged children to grow up and get an education.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two main locations in Mumbai, India</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">Run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT) since 1989</li>\r\n</ul>','Home','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 12:03:05','2014-03-12 12:03:05','',13,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/13-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(342,1,'2014-03-12 12:04:42','2014-03-12 12:04:42','[pagetitle]About Us[/pagetitle]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Safe and nurturing orphanages for girls to grow up in</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A school for slum and underprivileged children to get an education.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two main locations in Mumbai, India</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">Run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT) since 1989</li>\r\n</ul>','Home','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 12:04:42','2014-03-12 12:04:42','',13,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/13-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(343,1,'2014-03-12 12:45:02','2014-03-12 12:45:02','Our Locations:\r\n\r\nOur Postal Adresses:\r\n\r\nSend us an e-mail:\r\n\r\n[bestwebsoft_contact_form]','Contact','','inherit','open','open','','123-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 12:45:02','2014-03-12 12:45:02','',123,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/123-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(344,1,'2014-03-19 02:09:17','2014-03-19 02:09:17','Our Locations:  XXXX  Pictorial MAP GRAPHIC XXXX\n\nOur Postal Adresses:  XXX  Adresses of Church Pakadi,  Merces, Giriz  (within a box outline)  XXX\n\n[googlemap height=\"300\" zoom=\"13\" lat=\"19.0822507\" long=\"72.8812041\"]\n\nSend us an e-mail:\n\n[bestwebsoft_contact_form]\n\nAbout this website\n\n&nbsp;','Contact Us','','inherit','open','open','','123-autosave-v1','','','2014-03-19 02:09:17','2014-03-19 02:09:17','',123,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/123-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(345,1,'2014-03-12 12:47:17','2014-03-12 12:47:17','Our Locations:  XXXX  Pictorial MAP GRAPHIC XXXX\r\n\r\nOur Postal Adresses:  XXX  Adresses of Church Pakadi,  Merces, Giriz  (within a box outline)  XXX\r\n\r\nSend us an e-mail:\r\n\r\n[bestwebsoft_contact_form]','Contact','','inherit','open','open','','123-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 12:47:17','2014-03-12 12:47:17','',123,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/123-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(346,1,'2014-03-12 13:14:14','2014-03-12 13:14:14','<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-293\" alt=\"DSC01136 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>Tulsi was born November 2003 and her sister Gauri was born April 2005.  Both are living at the Sahar Orphanage.  They are in 3rd and 2nd standard respectively.  Their mother died in a road accident.  Their father had no job and was homeless so he brought the girls to the orphanage.   He hopes to collect them after they complete school through the 7th standard at Sahar,  by which time he hopes his personal situation will have improved.','Tulsi & Gauri Shetty','','inherit','open','open','','162-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:14:14','2014-03-12 13:14:14','',162,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/162-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(347,1,'2014-03-12 13:16:11','2014-03-12 13:16:11','<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Small.jpg\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-292\" alt=\"DSC01134 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Small.jpg\" width=\"480\" height=\"640\" /></a><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-293\" alt=\"DSC01136 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>Tulsi was born November 2003 and her sister Gauri was born April 2005.  Both are living at the Sahar Orphanage.  They are in 3rd and 2nd standard respectively.  Their mother died in a road accident.  Their father had no job and was homeless so he brought the girls to the orphanage.   He hopes to collect them after they complete school through the 7th standard at Sahar,  by which time he hopes his personal situation will have improved.','Tulsi & Gauri Shetty','','inherit','open','open','','162-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:16:11','2014-03-12 13:16:11','',162,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/162-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(348,1,'2014-03-12 13:17:50','2014-03-12 13:17:50','<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01140-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-294\" alt=\"DSC01140 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01140-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>Sneha was born September 2003.   She is currently healthy.  She has been living at the Sahar Orphanage since the age of 3 when she was brought there by her grandmother who still visits.\r\n\r\nHer father had burned her mother to death over a property dispute and spent some time in jail.  His brother bought for him his way out of jail within the corrupt system in India.  He is forbidden from seeing Sneha.  Her brother Sopnil is 2 years older.  He was living at the Merces Orphange but is currently at another orphanage.\r\n\r\nShe attends 3rd standard at the Sahar Orphanage School and is maintaining an average academic performance in her class of 50 students.','Sneha Borde','','inherit','open','open','','164-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:17:50','2014-03-12 13:17:50','',164,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/164-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(349,1,'2014-03-12 13:19:41','2014-03-12 13:19:41','<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01035-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-253\" alt=\"DSC01035 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01035-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>Preeti was born in April 2000.  She has been living at Merces Orphanage since the age of 5.   Her dad died of tuberculosis just before.   Her mother brought her to the orphange because she couldn\'t take care of her.  In 2013 her mother also died of tuberculosis.   Preeti has been treated and cured.\r\n\r\nPreeti is first in her class of 47 students at nearby St. Thomas High School where she takes Geography,  English,  History, Science, Math, Drawing and a computer class.  Her favorite subject is English.  She hopes to become a teacher someday.  She is very happy to be living at this orphanage and is greatful to the sisters for looking after her.','Preeti Kutade','','inherit','open','open','','154-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:19:41','2014-03-12 13:19:41','',154,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/154-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(350,1,'2014-03-12 13:21:14','2014-03-12 13:21:14','<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01037-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-254\" alt=\"DSC01037 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01037-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>Ruby was born in June 1999.   Both of her parents passed away of unknown causes.  She was living with her sister but upon her sister\'s marriage she was brought to the Merces Orphanage about a year ago.\r\n\r\nRuby\'s favorite subjects in school are Speech (in which she enters competitions) and Singing (for which she has won awards).  She hopes someday to be a doctor because it is \"a respectable career\".   She really values all the people caring for her at the orphanage and feels a sense of community.  She said she would rather stay at the orphanage than to go back to her previous life.','Ruby Kureshi','','inherit','open','open','','156-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:21:14','2014-03-12 13:21:14','',156,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/156-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(351,1,'2014-03-12 13:22:42','2014-03-12 13:22:42','<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01040-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-255\" alt=\"DSC01040 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01040-Small.jpg\" width=\"480\" height=\"640\" /></a>Supriya is currently in 6th standard and has lived at the Merces Orphanage since 2007.   When both her parents died of tuberculosis she was brought to the orphanage by her grandmother who  had to go to work and had no means to support her.   She is expected to return to her grandmother after 10th grade but she is not sure she wants to go back.   She has one brother who is 14 years old who lives in another orphanage and visits on Sundays.\r\n\r\nSupriya attends St. Anthony\'s Convent School where she is average in her class of 80 kids.  She hopes to be an aritist someday.','Supriya Naka','','inherit','open','open','','158-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:22:42','2014-03-12 13:22:42','',158,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/158-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(352,1,'2014-03-12 13:23:23','2014-03-12 13:23:23','<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01041-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-256\" alt=\"DSC01041 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01041-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>Arti was born in September 1998.  Her father divorced her mother and ran away.  Her mother works as a live-in-maid in someone\'s house and is unable to have Arti with her but visits her on Sundays.\r\n\r\nShe is currently in the 8th standard and has lived at Merces Orphanage since 2009.  She hopes someday to become a police officer because she \"wants to enforce justice\".','Arti Gaikwade','','inherit','open','open','','160-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:23:23','2014-03-12 13:23:23','',160,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/160-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(353,1,'2014-03-12 13:27:21','2014-03-12 13:27:21','&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Tulsi Shetty<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-292\" alt=\"DSC01134 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Small.jpg\" width=\"480\" height=\"640\" /></a></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\nGauri Shetty<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-293\" alt=\"DSC01136 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" />Tulsi was born November 2003 and her sister Gauri was born April 2005.  Both are living at the Sahar Orphanage.  They are in 3rd and 2nd standard respectively.  Their mother died in a road accident.  Their father had no job and was homeless so he brought the girls to the orphanage.   He hopes to collect them after they complete school through the 7th standard at Sahar,  by which time he hopes his personal situation will have improved.</p>','Tulsi & Gauri Shetty','','inherit','open','open','','162-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:27:21','2014-03-12 13:27:21','',162,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/162-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(355,1,'2014-03-12 13:31:23','2014-03-12 13:31:23','<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sister Eliza with Muk<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01196-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-236\" alt=\"DSC01196 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01196-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sister Eliza comes from a Christian Indian family in Goa.  She came to Mumbai to study Social Work.  She completed college and a M.A. degree in Social Work.  She was very much drawn to helping the abandoned and poor.  During this time, around 1990,  she was introduced to Sr. Paulette and became the first Sister to join the HMBT.  For more than 20 years now she has been a strong pillar to the order.  Today she spends most of her time running the day to day affairs of the Sahar Orphanage.  She also teaches at a nearby private school,  and through this employment,  brings in financial support to run the orphanage.</p>\n&nbsp;','Eliza','','inherit','open','open','','23-autosave-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:31:23','2014-03-12 13:31:23','',23,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/23-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(356,1,'2014-03-12 13:30:09','2014-03-12 13:30:09','<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01196-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-236\" alt=\"DSC01196 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01196-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>Sister Eliza comes from a Christian Indian family in Goa.  She came to Mumbai to study Social Work.  She completed college and a M.A. degree in Social Work.  She was very much drawn to helping the abandoned and poor.  During this time, around 1990,  she was introduced to Sr. Paulette and became the first Sister to join the HMBT.  For more than 20 years now she has been a strong pillar to the order.  Today she spends most of her time running the day to day affairs of the Sahar Orphanage.  She also teaches at a nearby private school,  and through this employment,  brings in financial support to run the orphanage.</p>\r\n&nbsp;','Eliza','','inherit','open','open','','23-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:30:09','2014-03-12 13:30:09','',23,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/23-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(357,1,'2014-03-12 13:31:46','2014-03-12 13:31:46','<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sister Eliza with Muskan<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01196-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-236\" alt=\"DSC01196 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01196-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sister Eliza comes from a Christian Indian family in Goa.  She came to Mumbai to study Social Work.  She completed college and a M.A. degree in Social Work.  She was very much drawn to helping the abandoned and poor.  During this time, around 1990,  she was introduced to Sr. Paulette and became the first Sister to join the HMBT.  For more than 20 years now she has been a strong pillar to the order.  Today she spends most of her time running the day to day affairs of the Sahar Orphanage.  She also teaches at a nearby private school,  and through this employment,  brings in financial support to run the orphanage.</p>\r\n&nbsp;','Eliza','','inherit','open','open','','23-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:31:46','2014-03-12 13:31:46','',23,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/23-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(358,1,'2014-03-12 13:32:18','2014-03-12 13:32:18','<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01043-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-257\" alt=\"DSC01043 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01043-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sr. Paulette comes from a Christian Indian family from the island of Mauritus.  In her youth she decided to become a nun and came to Calcutta to join Mother Teresa.  For about 20 years she worked with Mother Teresa mainly helping women and children and doing family planning work.  She developed a severe back condition which required hospitalization. She was sent to a Mumbai hospital where she spent several months.  When she emerged from recuperation Mother Teresa urged her to remain in Mumbai in a life of service.  This is how, in 1989,  she became the foundress of a new order of nuns called the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.  Today the order contains about 40 nuns;  about 10 of these are directly working with Sr. Paulette at the orphanages.</p>\r\n&nbsp;','Paulette','','inherit','open','open','','25-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:32:18','2014-03-12 13:32:18','',25,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/25-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(359,1,'2014-03-12 13:35:11','2014-03-12 13:35:11','<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01143-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-295\" alt=\"DSC01143 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01143-Small.jpg\" width=\"480\" height=\"640\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Amma is the resident caretaker of the orphans at Sahar.  She is in her 70’s, a widow.  She was shunned by her own family.  This is how she came to  join the family of the HMBT nuns and orphans for whom she has worked tirelessly for the past 15 years.  She is responsible for cooking, feeding, bathing and dressing the kids,  and being a grandmother to all of them.</p>','Amma','','inherit','open','open','','137-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:35:11','2014-03-12 13:35:11','',137,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/137-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(360,1,'2014-03-12 13:43:31','2014-03-12 13:43:31','&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Tulsi Shetty<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-292\" alt=\"DSC01134 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Small.jpg\" width=\"480\" height=\"640\" /></a></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Gauri Shetty<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-293\" alt=\"DSC01136 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" />Tulsi was born November 2003 and her sister Gauri was born April 2005.  Both are living at the Sahar Orphanage.  They are in 3rd and 2nd standard respectively.  Their mother died in a road accident.  Their father had no job and was homeless so he brought the girls to the orphanage.   He hopes to collect them after they complete school through the 7th standard at Sahar,  by which time he hopes his personal situation will have improved.</p>','Tulsi & Gauri Shetty','','inherit','open','open','','162-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:43:31','2014-03-12 13:43:31','',162,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/162-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(362,1,'2014-03-12 13:48:40','2014-03-12 13:48:40','<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, and up to recently,  it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is in the Church Pakadi slum).</span></p>\r\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to local social service agencies.  Often,  orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses for the HMBT order but grew to become orphanages around 1996, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 nuns to recently about 40 nuns.  About 10 of these are involved with the orphanages and the remainder are doing parish work in other states in India.\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any male residential mentors or father figures.  Also,  it was not possible to maintain separate living quarters for boys and girls.    There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage.   Over the years the school became more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent and nearby slums.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  A typical classroom is about 200 square feet and holds about 30 kids.  The teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:48:40','2014-03-12 13:48:40','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(361,1,'2014-03-12 13:48:03','2014-03-12 13:48:03','<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, and up to recently,  it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is in the Church Pakadi slum).</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary13.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-thumbnail wp-image-85\" alt=\"diary13\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary13-150x150.jpg\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a></p>\r\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to local social service agencies.  Often,  orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses for the HMBT order but grew to become orphanages around 1996, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 nuns to recently about 40 nuns.  About 10 of these are involved with the orphanages and the remainder are doing parish work in other states in India.\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any male residential mentors or father figures.  Also,  it was not possible to maintain separate living quarters for boys and girls.    There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage.   Over the years the school became more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent and nearby slums.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  A typical classroom is about 200 square feet and holds about 30 kids.  The teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:48:03','2014-03-12 13:48:03','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(363,1,'2014-03-12 13:58:20','2014-03-12 13:58:20','<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The HMBT order has relied entirely on receiving outside donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from any parent organization.   The HMBT is registered as an Indian NGO under the secular name Sneha Jewan Kendra which means Love and Life Center.  Effort is currently underway to register Sneha Jewan Kendra in the United States as a charitable 501 C 3 organization.</span>\r\n\r\nOn this page you can see a list of the major current needs at the orphanages.  Your contribution is greatly appreciated.\r\n\r\n<form action=\"https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr\" method=\"post\" target=\"_top\"><input type=\"hidden\" name=\"cmd\" value=\"_s-xclick\" />\r\n<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"hosted_button_id\" value=\"BGG3VL42SCA5L\" />\r\n<input type=\"image\" alt=\"PayPal - The safer, easier way to pay online!\" name=\"submit\" src=\"https://www.paypalobjects.com/en_US/i/btn/btn_donateCC_LG.gif\" />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://www.paypalobjects.com/en_US/i/scr/pixel.gif\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" border=\"0\" /></form>','Support Us','','inherit','open','open','','11-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:58:20','2014-03-12 13:58:20','',11,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/11-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(364,1,'2014-03-12 13:58:57','2014-03-12 13:58:57','Our Locations:  XXXX  Pictorial MAP GRAPHIC XXXX\r\n\r\nOur Postal Adresses:  XXX  Adresses of Church Pakadi,  Merces, Giriz  (within a box outline)  XXX\r\n\r\nSend us an e-mail:\r\n\r\n[bestwebsoft_contact_form]','Contact Us','','inherit','open','open','','123-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 13:58:57','2014-03-12 13:58:57','',123,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/123-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(365,1,'2014-03-12 14:05:53','2014-03-12 14:05:53','*  The main orphanage house at Merces has a leaking roof over the room in which  the kids have shelves to put their school bags and books.  The sisters would like to remedy this by constructing a covered terrace above this room which will also give a space to hang up all the laundry to dry.  Currently the clothes are washed by hand as part of the chores of the orphans.   There is no covered place to hang laundry for drying - so there is no way to dry clothes when it rains.    The estimated cost for this project is: _________\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01193-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-233\" alt=\"DSC01193 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01193-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n* The electrical wiring in the main orphanage house at Merces needs to be replaced.  Currently there are exposed wires and the wires are in dis-repair.   The estimated cost for this project is:_________\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01195-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-235\" alt=\"DSC01195 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01195-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" 