in 3rd and 2nd standard respectively.  Their mother died in a road accident.  Their father had no job and was homeless so he brought the girls to the orphanage.   He hopes to collect them after they complete school through the 7th standard at Sahar,  by which time he hopes his personal situation will have improved.</p>','Tulsi & Gauri Shetty','','inherit','open','open','','162-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 18:27:45','2014-03-12 18:27:45','',162,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/162-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(379,1,'2014-03-12 18:28:04','2014-03-12 18:28:04','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Custom.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-374 alignleft\" alt=\"DSC01134 (Custom)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Custom.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Custom.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-375\" alt=\"DSC01136 (Custom)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Custom.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"240\" /></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">                                                                                                                                                               Gauri Shetty</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">               Tulsi Shetty</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tulsi was born November 2003 and her sister Gauri was born April 2005.  Both are living at the Sahar Orphanage.  They are in 3rd and 2nd standard respectively.  Their mother died in a road accident.  Their father had no job and was homeless so he brought the girls to the orphanage.   He hopes to collect them after they complete school through the 7th standard at Sahar,  by which time he hopes his personal situation will have improved.</p>','Tulsi & Gauri Shetty','','inherit','open','open','','162-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 18:28:04','2014-03-12 18:28:04','',162,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/162-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(381,1,'2014-03-13 02:26:48','2014-03-13 02:26:48','<strong>Sahar Slums School:</strong>\r\n\r\n[right][carousel name=\"school\"][/right]\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They have worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage House which doubles as classroom spaces.\r\n\r\nOver the years this school has become more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent slums.  Today, 300 students representing multiple grade levels up to 7th standard attend this school, all crammed in a space not more than 2000 square feet.  When the school day is over the space reverts to being the living quarters for the 30  resident orphans and their caretakers.\r\n\r\nThe teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees ($ 7) per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option. They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools,  and the nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families. The HBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the Sahar slum kids would receive no education.\r\n\r\n<strong>School for Merces - Giriz Orphans:</strong>\r\n\r\nAt the Merces - Giriz orphanages the girls attend  schools in the local community.  They all take a bus or walk to get to school.   Their school fees are borne by the HBT along with any contribution given by family members of the orphans.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-617\" alt=\"DSC01053 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>','School','','publish','open','open','','school','','','2014-04-11 13:14:00','2014-04-11 13:14:00','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=381',3,'page','',0),(612,1,'2014-03-27 17:16:30','2014-03-27 17:16:30','Sahar School:\r\n\r\n[right][carousel name=\"school][/right]\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They have worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage House which doubles as classroom spaces.   Over the years the school has become more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent slums.  Today, 300 students representing multiple grade levels up to 7th standard are all packed tightly in a space not more than 2000 square feet.  When the school day is over the space reverts to being the living quarters for the 30  resident orphans and their caretakers.\r\n\r\nThe teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees ($ 7)  per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the Sahar slum kids would receive no education.','School','','inherit','open','open','','381-revision-v1','','','2014-03-27 17:16:30','2014-03-27 17:16:30','',381,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/381-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(611,1,'2014-03-27 17:16:18','2014-03-27 17:16:18','Sahar School:      xxx  content pending  xxx\r\n\r\n[right][carousel name=\"school][/right]\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They have worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage House which doubles as classroom spaces.   Over the years the school has become more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent slums.  Today, 300 students representing multiple grade levels up to 7th standard are all packed tightly in a space not more than 2000 square feet.  When the school day is over the space reverts to being the living quarters for the 30  resident orphans and their caretakers.\r\n\r\nThe teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees ($ 7)  per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the Sahar slum kids would receive no education.','School','','inherit','open','open','','381-revision-v1','','','2014-03-27 17:16:18','2014-03-27 17:16:18','',381,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/381-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(382,1,'2014-03-13 02:26:48','2014-03-13 02:26:48','','School','','inherit','open','open','','381-revision-v1','','','2014-03-13 02:26:48','2014-03-13 02:26:48','',381,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/381-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(383,1,'2014-03-13 02:27:56','2014-03-13 02:27:56','Main locations page.','Orphanages','','inherit','open','open','','222-revision-v1','','','2014-03-13 02:27:56','2014-03-13 02:27:56','',222,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/222-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(384,1,'2014-03-13 02:28:43','2014-03-13 02:28:43','There are about 30 orphans at Sahar and about 100 at Merces-Giriz.  They range from 3 years to 16 years old.  Their parents have died either due to disease, violent crime,  self neglect,  or are in prison.\r\n\r\nSome of the kids are not \"orphans\" but have been brought by a parent or family member because they are physically or financially unable to care for them.  Often, there will be one surviving parent or a distant relative that continues to visit their child at the orphanages and this individual will eventually accept the child back.   But while they are there, the HMBT Sisters care for them completely.\r\n\r\nOn a typical day they will arise at 5:30-6:00 am.  After eating breakfast they will get dressed and ready for school which  goes till the early afternoon.   At Sahar the school is within the orphanage house itself;  at Merces-Giriz the kids take a bus or walk to nearby independent schools.   In the mid-afternoon there is additonal tutoring by a paid teacher at Sahar and by volunteer local college students at Merces-Giriz.  In the late afternoon the kids all do homework,  chores, have play time,  take baths, eat dinner and have prayer time.  They typically go to bed around 9 pm.    On Sundays, there is extra time for watching T.V.,  having a party, music, dance,  and also visits by family members or persons from the community.\r\n\r\nOn this page you will find some profiles typical of the orphans.','Orphan Profiles','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-v1','','','2014-03-13 02:28:43','2014-03-13 02:28:43','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/151-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(385,1,'2014-03-13 02:32:15','2014-03-13 02:32:15','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Custom.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-374 alignleft\" alt=\"DSC01134 (Custom)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Custom.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Custom.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-375\" alt=\"DSC01136 (Custom)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Custom.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"240\" /></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">                                                                                                                                                               Gauri Shetty</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">                     Tulsi Shetty</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tulsi was born November 2003 and her sister Gauri was born April 2005.  Both are living at the Sahar Orphanage.  They are in 3rd and 2nd standard respectively.  Their mother died in a road accident.  Their father had no job and was homeless so he brought the girls to the orphanage.   He hopes to collect them after they complete school through the 7th standard at Sahar,  by which time he hopes his personal situation will have improved.</p>','Tulsi & Gauri Shetty','','inherit','open','open','','162-revision-v1','','','2014-03-13 02:32:15','2014-03-13 02:32:15','',162,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/162-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(404,1,'2014-03-13 13:18:28','2014-03-13 13:18:28','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Custom.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-374 alignleft\" alt=\"DSC01134 (Custom)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Custom.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Custom.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-375\" alt=\"DSC01136 (Custom)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploa