 their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7190-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-457\" alt=\"DSCF7190 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7190-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThen, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 nuns to recently about 40 nuns.  About 10 of these are involved with the orphanages and the remainder are doing parish work in other states in India.\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any male residential mentors or father figures.  Also,  it was not possible to maintain separate living quarters for boys and girls.    There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage.   Over the years the school became more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent and nearby slums.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  A typical classroom is about 200 square feet and holds about 30 kids.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7229-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-461\" alt=\"DSCF7229 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7229-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-03-19 01:26:24','2014-03-19 01:26:24','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(464,1,'2014-03-19 01:31:33','2014-03-19 01:31:33','','DSCF7475 (Mobile)','','inherit','open','open','','dscf7475-mobile','','','2014-03-19 01:31:33','2014-03-19 01:31:33','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7475-Mobile.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(465,1,'2014-03-19 01:32:33','2014-03-19 01:32:33','<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The missionary work of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, and up to recently,  it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is in the Church Pakadi slum).</span></p>\r\nLiving and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition,\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7610-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-451\" alt=\"DSCF7610 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7610-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nlack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7590-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-455\" alt=\"DSCF7590 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7590-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThey went door to door and did counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance. Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to local social service agencies.  Often,  orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7598-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-453\" alt=\"DSCF7598 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7598-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nand the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses for the HMBT order but grew to become orphanages around 1996, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF6974-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-459\" alt=\"DSCF6974 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF6974-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7190-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-457\" alt=\"DSCF7190 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7190-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>             <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7475-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-464\" alt=\"DSCF7475 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7475-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThen, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 nuns to recently about 40 nuns.  About 10 of these are involved with the orphanages and the remainder are doing parish work in other states in India.\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any male residential mentors or father figures.  Also,  it was not possible to maintain separate living quarters for boys and girls.    There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage.   Over the years the school became more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent and nearby slums.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  A typical classroom is about 200 square feet and holds about 30 kids.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7229-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-461\" alt=\"DSCF7229 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7229-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-03-19 01:32:33','2014-03-19 01:32:33','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(466,1,'2014-03-19 01:33:40','2014-03-19 01:33:40','<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The missionary work of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, and up to recently,  it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is in the Church Pakadi slum).</span></p>\r\nLiving and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition,\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7610-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-451\" alt=\"DSCF7610 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7610-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nlack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/