it','open','open','','25-revision-v1','','','2014-03-24 01:54:44','2014-03-24 01:54:44','',25,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/25-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(553,1,'2014-03-24 01:54:15','2014-03-24 01:54:15','<p dir=\"ltr\">[left]<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01043-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-257\" alt=\"DSC01043 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01043-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>[/left]</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sr. Paulette comes from a Christian Indian family from the island of Mauritus.  In her youth she decided to become a nun and came to Calcutta to join Mother Teresa.  For about 20 years she worked with Mother Teresa mainly helping women and children and doing family planning work.  She developed a severe back condition which required hospitalization. She was sent to a Mumbai hospital where she spent several months.  When she emerged from recuperation Mother Teresa urged her to remain in Mumbai in a life of service.  This is how, in 1989,  she became the foundress of a new order of nuns called the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.  Today the order contains about 40 nuns;  about 10 of these are directly working with Sr. Paulette at the orphanages.</p>\r\n&nbsp;','Sr. Paulette','','inherit','open','open','','25-revision-v1','','','2014-03-24 01:54:15','2014-03-24 01:54:15','',25,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/25-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(555,1,'2014-03-24 04:05:53','2014-03-24 04:05:53','','1000 x 400 DSCF7472','','inherit','open','open','','1000-x-400-dscf7472','','','2014-03-24 04:05:53','2014-03-24 04:05:53','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/1000-x-400-DSCF7472.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(557,1,'2014-03-24 04:26:18','2014-03-24 04:26:18','','1000 x 400 DSCF7190','','inherit','open','open','','1000-x-4