ed projects.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed October 2013</span>:    The rusting and broken down stairs at the Merces Orphanage house needed replacement.  It was the main passage way for 100 orphans to get to their upstairs living quarters.  The cost of this project was 232,500 Rupees (aproximately $ 4,850).   This entire project was funded by a single benefactor Dr. Judy Macy from Grosse Ile,  Michigan.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01021-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSC01021 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01021-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed late 2012</span>:   Power outages at the Merces Orphanage are frequent, almost daily for brief periods of time.   During this time a back-up electric battery system was needed to power several light bulbs.  The cost of this project was 52,000 Rupees (approximately $ 1100).   This entire project was funded by a single benefactor Dr. Judy Macy from Grosse Ile,  Michigan.\r\n\r\nxxx PHOTO PENDING xxx\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed Fall 2011</span>:   Water used for personal hygeine and washing clothes at the Merces Orphanage house was not sanitary;  it was also uncomfortably cold for bathing.  The reasons of this are described in this narrative.  The solution involved sealing the supply well,  then filtering and pumping contaminated well water to a solar heated water tank installed on the roof of the orphanage house.  From here the water is gravity delivered to the first floor.  Not only is the water clean and safe but also warm for bathing in the winter months.  The cost of this project was 200,000 Rupees (approximately $ 4900).   The funds for this project were raised from many individual donors including the congregation of the Zen Buddhist Temple of Ann Arbor, Michigan.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01049-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-743\" alt=\"DSC01049 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01049-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Recently Funded','','inherit','open','open','','509-revision-v1','','','2014-04-04 14:02:09','2014-04-04 14:02:09','',509,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/509-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(746,1,'2014-04-04 14:03:05','2014-04-04 14:03:05','This page will profile recently funded projects.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed October 2013</span>:    The rusting and broken down stairs at the Merces Orphanage house needed replacement.  It was the main passage way for 100 orphans to get to their upstairs living quarters.  The cost of this project was 232,500 Rupees (aproximately $ 4,850).   This entire project was funded by a single benefactor Dr. Judy Macy from Grosse Ile,  Michigan.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01021-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSC01021 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01021-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed late 2012</span>:   Power outages at the Merces Orphanage are frequent, almost daily for brief periods of time.   During this time a back-up electric battery system was needed to power several light bulbs.  The cost of this project was 52,000 Rupees (approximately $ 1100).   This entire project was funded by a single benefactor Dr. Judy Macy from Grosse Ile,  Michigan.\r\n\r\nxxx PHOTO PENDING xxx\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed Fall 2011</span>:   Water used for personal hygeine and washing clothes at the Merces Orphanage house was not sanitary;  it was also uncomfortably cold for bathing.  The reasons of this are described in this narrative.  The solution involved sealing the supply well,  then filtering and pumping contaminated well water to a solar heated water tank installed on the roof of the orphanage house.  From here the water is gravity delivered to the first floor.  Not only is the water clean and safe but also warm for bathing in the winter months.  The cost of this project was 200,000 Rupees (approx. $ 4900).   The funds for this project were raised from many individual donors including the congregation of the Zen Buddhist Temple of Ann Arbor, Michigan.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01049-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-743\" alt=\"DSC01049 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01049-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Recently Funded','','inherit','open','open','','509-revision-v1','','','2014-04-04 14:03:05','2014-04-04 14:03:05','',509,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/509-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(747,1,'2014-04-04 14:07:34','2014-04-04 14:07:34','','DSC01193 (Mobile)','','inherit','open','open','','dsc01193-mobile','','','2014-04-04 14:07:34','2014-04-04 14:07:34','',169,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01193-Mobile.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(748,1,'2014-04-04 14:07:36','2014-04-04 14:07:36','','DSC01195 (Mobile)','','inherit','open','open','','dsc01195-mobile','','','2014-04-04 14:07:36','2014-04-04 14:07:36','',169,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01195-Mobile.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(830,1,'2014-04-13 18:22:05','2014-04-13 18:22:05','The left side bar of this page will take you to some typical orphan profiles.\r\n\r\nThere are about 30 orphans at Sahar and about 100 at Merces-Giriz.  They range from 3 years to 16 years old.  Their parents have died either due to disease, violent crime,  self neglect,  or are in prison.\r\n\r\nSome of the kids are not \"orphans\" but have been brought by a parent or family member because they are physically or financially unable to care for them.  Often, there will be one surviving parent or a distant relative that continues to visit their child at the orphanages and this individual will eventually accept the child back.   But while they are there, the HBT Sisters care for them completely.\r\n\r\nOn a typical day they will arise between 5:30-6:00 am.  After eating breakfast they will get dressed and ready for school which  goes through the early afternoon Monday to Saturday.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01209-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-646\" alt=\"DSC01209 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01209-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"427\" /></a>\r\n\r\nAt Sahar the school is within the orphanage house itself;  at Merces-Giriz the kids take a bus or walk to nearby independent schools.   In the mid-afternoon there is additonal tutoring by a paid teacher at Sahar and by volunteer local college students at Merces-Giriz.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01175-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-645\" alt=\"DSC01175 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01175-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nIn the late afternoon the kids all do homework,  <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01029-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-643\" alt=\"DSC01029 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01029-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nchores,   <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01027-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-642\" alt=\"DSC01027 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01027-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nthen have play time, take baths, eat dinner and have prayer time.  They typically go to bed around 9 pm.    On Sundays, there is extra time for watching T.V.,  having a party, music, dance,\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01054-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSC01054 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01054-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nand also visits by family members or persons from the community.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Orphan Profiles','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-v1','','','2014-04-13 18:22:05','2014-04-13 18:22:05','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/151-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(750,1,'2014-04-04 14:09:37','2014-04-04 14:09:37','*  The main orphanage house at Merces has a leaking roof over the room in which  the kids have shelves to put their school bags and books.  The sisters would like to remedy this by constructing a covered terrace above this room which will also give a space to hang up all the laundry to dry.  Currently the clothes are washed by hand as part of the chores of the orphans.   There is no covered place to hang laundry for drying - so there is no way to dry clothes when it rains.    The estimated cost for this project is: _________\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01193-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSC01193 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01193-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n* The electrical wiring in the main orphanage house at Merces needs to be replaced.  Currently there are exposed wires and some of the wires are in disrepair.   The estimated cost for this project is:_________\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01195-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-748\" alt=\"DSC01195 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01195-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Current Needs','','inherit','open','open','','169-revision-v1','','','2014-04-04 14:09:37','2014-04-04 14:09:37','',169,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/169-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(751,1,'2014-04-04 14:13:01','2014-04-04 14:13:01','*  The main orphanage house at Merces has a leaking roof over the room in which 100 orphans store their school bags and books.   A covered terrace needs to be constructed above this room.  This terrace will also functions as a space to hang up all the laundry to dry.  Currently the clothes are washed by hand as part of the chores of the orphans.   There is no covered place to hang laundry for drying - so there is no way to dry clothes when it rains, especially in the monsoon season.    The estimated cost for this project is: _________\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01193-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSC01193 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01193-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n* The electrical wiring in the main orphanage house at Merces needs to be replaced.  Currently there are exposed wires and some of the wires are in disrepair.   The estimated cost for this project is:_________\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01195-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-748\" alt=\"DSC01195 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01195-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Current Needs','','inherit','open','open','','169-revision-v1','','','2014-04-04 14:13:01','2014-04-04 14:13:01','',169,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/169-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(766,1,'2014-04-06 21:54:39','2014-04-06 21:54:39','','DSC01045 cropped','','inherit','open','open','','dsc01045-cropped','','','2014-04-06 21:54:39','2014-04-06 21:54:39','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01045-cropped.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(767,1,'2014-04-06 22:02:56','2014-04-06 22:02:56','','Invertor cropped','','inherit','open','open','','invertor-cropped','','','2014-04-06 22:02:56','2014-04-06 22:02:56','',509,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Invertor-cropped.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(770,1,'2014-04-06 22:14:01','2014-04-06 22:14:01','','Solar Water Tank','','inherit','open','open','','solar-water-tank','','','2014-04-06 22:14:01','2014-04-06 22:14:01','',509,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Solar-Water-Tank.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(755,1,'2014-04-04 21:11:14','2014-04-04 21:11:14','','Sr. Paulette with kids','','inherit','open','open','','sr-paulette-with-kids-2','','','2014-04-04 21:11:14','2014-04-04 21:11:14','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Sr.-Paulette-with-kids1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(757,1,'2014-04-04 21:15:24','2014-04-04 21:15:24','<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The Handmaids Orphanages and School were started by nuns (sisters) of an order known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT). </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The missionary work of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, and up to recently,  there were only two nuns in the order,   Sr. Paulette and Sr. Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas bordering the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums.</span></p>\r\nLiving and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: not having enough food leading to severe malnutrition,\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7610-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-451\" alt=\"DSCF7610 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7610-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nliving in ramshackle huts without electricity or a bathroom,\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7590-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-455\" alt=\"DSCF7590 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7590-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nand children not going to school.   They went door to door to do counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance. Through their outreach the Sisters became known in the area and to local social service agencies.  Often,  orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually they realized they would have to start  their own orphanage.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Sr.-Paulette-with-kids1.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-755\" alt=\"Sr. Paulette with kids\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Sr.-Paulette-with-kids1.jpg\" width=\"359\" height=\"465\" /></a>\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum the Sisters were taking care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager slum hut.  Upon her death her property, which had been willed to the local church, was purchased by the Sisters.  This became their home base,  their convent house in the slum.    Around that same time they received a donation of land in a suburb of Mumbai called Merces &amp; Giriz  on which they were able to build a larger convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces - Giriz sites were eventually developed to become orphanages and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.\r\n\r\nThe HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Sisters were helped greatly by charitable donations from the Mumbai division of  J.P. Morgan Bank.  They were able to use this large assistance to do much needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF6974-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-459\" alt=\"DSCF6974 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF6974-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nOver the years,  the order of nuns of the HMBT has grown from just 2 nuns to recently about 40 nuns.  About 10 of these are involved with the orphanages in the Mumbai area and the remainder are doing different parish work in other parts of India.\r\n\r\nThe sisters have had to overcome many challenges in being responsible for all the orphans under their care.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01017-resized.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-659\" alt=\"DSC01017 resized\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01017-resized.jpg\" width=\"490\" height=\"368\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThen, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their missionary work diligently.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01016-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-605\" alt=\"DSC01016 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01016-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any male residential mentors or father figures.  Also,  it was not possible to maintain separate living quarters for boys and girls.\r\n\r\nThere is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claim them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is needed and maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They have worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage House which doubles as classroom spaces.   Over the years this school has become more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent slums.  Today, 300 students representing multiple grade levels up to 7th standard attend this school,  all crammed in a space not more than 2000 square feet.  When the school day is over the space reverts to being the living quarters for the 30  resident orphans and their caretakers.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7229-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-461\" alt=\"DSCF7229 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7229-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees ($ 7)  per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the Sahar slum kids would receive no education.\r\n\r\nAt the Merces - Giriz orphanages the girls attend  schools in the local community.  They all take a bus or walk to get to school.   Their school fees are borne by the HMBT along with any contribution given by family members of the orphans.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-617\" alt=\"DSC01053 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-04-04 21:15:24','2014-04-04 21:15:24','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(756,1,'2014-04-04 21:12:29','2014-04-04 21:12:29','<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The Handmaids Orphanages and School were started by nuns (sisters) of an order known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT). </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The missionary work of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, and up to recently,  there were only two nuns in the order,   Sr. Paulette and Sr. Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas bordering the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums.</span></p>\r\nLiving and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: not having enough food leading to severe malnutrition,\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7610-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-451\" alt=\"DSCF7610 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7610-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nliving in ramshackle huts without electricity or a bathroom,\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7590-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-455\" alt=\"DSCF7590 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7590-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nand children not going to school.   They went door to door to do counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance. Through their outreach the Sisters became known in the area and to local social service agencies.  Often,  orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Sr.-Paulette-with-kids1.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-755\" alt=\"Sr. Paulette with kids\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Sr.-Paulette-with-kids1.jpg\" width=\"359\" height=\"465\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7598-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-453\" alt=\"DSCF7598 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7598-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nand the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually they realized they would have to start  their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum the Sisters were taking care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager slum hut.  Upon her death her property, which had been willed to the local church, was purchased by the Sisters.  This became their home base,  their convent house in the slum.    Around that same time they received a donation of land in a suburb of Mumbai called Merces &amp; Giriz  on which they were able to build a larger convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces - Giriz sites were eventually developed to become orphanages and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.\r\n\r\nThe HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Sisters were helped greatly by charitable donations from the Mumbai division of  J.P. Morgan Bank.  They were able to use this large assistance to do much needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF6974-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-459\" alt=\"DSCF6974 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF6974-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nOver the years,  the order of nuns of the HMBT has grown from just 2 nuns to recently about 40 nuns.  About 10 of these are involved with the orphanages in the Mumbai area and the remainder are doing different parish work in other parts of India.\r\n\r\nThe sisters have had to overcome many challenges in being responsible for all the orphans under their care.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01017-resized.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-659\" alt=\"DSC01017 resized\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01017-resized.jpg\" width=\"490\" height=\"368\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThen, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their missionary work diligently.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01016-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-605\" alt=\"DSC01016 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01016-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any male residential mentors or father figures.  Also,  it was not possible to maintain separate living quarters for boys and girls.\r\n\r\nThere is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claim them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is needed and maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They have worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage House which doubles as classroom spaces.   Over the years this school has become more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent slums.  Today, 300 students representing multiple grade levels up to 7th standard attend this school,  all crammed in a space not more than 2000 square feet.  When the school day is over the space reverts to being the living quarters for the 30  resident orphans and their caretakers.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7229-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-461\" alt=\"DSCF7229 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7229-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees ($ 7)  per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the Sahar slum kids would receive no education.\r\n\r\nAt the Merces - Giriz orphanages the girls attend  schools in the local community.  They all take a bus or walk to get to school.   Their school fees are borne by the HMBT along with any contribution given by family members of the orphans.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-617\" alt=\"DSC01053 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-04-04 21:12:29','2014-04-04 21:12:29','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(759,1,'2014-04-04 21:22:14','2014-04-04 21:22:14','This page will profile recently funded projects.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed October 2013</span>:    The rusting and broken down stairs at the Merces Orphanage house needed replacement.  It was the main passage way for 100 orphans to get to their upstairs living quarters.  The cost of this project was 232,500 Rupees (aproximately $ 4,850).   This entire project was funded by a single benefactor Dr. Judy Macy from Grosse Ile,  Michigan.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01021-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSC01021 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01021-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed late 2012</span>:   Power outages at the Merces Orphanage are frequent, almost daily for brief periods of time.   During this time a back-up electric battery system was needed to power several light bulbs.  The cost of this project was 52,000 Rupees (approximately $ 1100).   This entire project was funded by a single benefactor Dr. Judy Macy from Grosse Ile,  Michigan.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Invertor.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-758\" alt=\"Invertor\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Invertor.jpg\" width=\"733\" height=\"484\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed Fall 2011</span>:   Water used for personal hygeine and washing clothes at the Merces Orphanage house was not sanitary;  it was also uncomfortably cold for bathing.  The reasons of this are described in this narrative.  The solution involved sealing the supply well,  then filtering and pumping contaminated well water to a solar heated water tank installed on the roof of the orphanage house.  From here the water is gravity delivered to the first floor.  Not only is the water clean and safe but also warm for bathing in the winter months.  The cost of this project was 200,000 Rupees (approx. $ 4900).   The funds for this project were raised from many individual donors including the congregation of the Zen Buddhist Temple of Ann Arbor, Michigan.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01049-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-743\" alt=\"DSC01049 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01049-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Recently Funded','','inherit','open','open','','509-revision-v1','','','2014-04-04 21:22:14','2014-04-04 21:22:14','',509,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/509-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(771,1,'2014-04-06 22:14:51','2014-04-06 22:14:51','This page will profile recently funded projects.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed October 2013</span>:    The rusting and broken down stairs at the Merces Orphanage house needed replacement.  It was the main passage way for 100 orphans to get to their upstairs living quarters.  The cost of this project was 232,500 Rupees (aproximately $ 4,850).   This entire project was funded by a single benefactor who wishes to remain anonymous.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01021-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSC01021 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01021-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed late 2012</span>:   Power outages at the Merces Orphanage are frequent, almost daily for brief periods of time.   During this time a 