hanage.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Sr.-Paulette-with-kids1.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-755\" alt=\"Sr. Paulette with kids\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Sr.-Paulette-with-kids1.jpg\" width=\"359\" height=\"465\" /></a>\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum the Sisters were taking care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager slum hut.  Upon her death her property, which had been willed to the local church, was purchased by the Sisters.  This became their home base,  their convent house in the slum.    Around that same time they received a donation of land in a suburb of Mumbai called Merces &amp; Giriz  on which they were able to build a larger convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces - Giriz sites were eventually developed to become orphanages and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.\r\n\r\nThe HBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Sisters were helped greatly by charitable donations from the Mumbai division of  J.P. Morgan Bank.  They were able to use this large assistance to do much needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF6974-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-459\" alt=\"DSCF6974 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF6974-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nOver the years,  the order of nuns of the HMBT has grown from just 2 nuns to recently about 40 nuns.  About 10 of these are involved with the orphanages in the Mumbai area and the remainder are doing different parish work in other parts of India.\r\n\r\nThe sisters have had to overcome many challenges in being responsible for all the orphans under their care.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01017-resized.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-659\" alt=\"DSC01017 resized\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01017-resized.jpg\" width=\"490\" height=\"368\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThen, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night after attending to their missionary work diligently.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01016-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-605\" alt=\"DSC01016 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01016-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any male residential mentors or father figures.  Also,  it was not possible to maintain separate living quarters for boys and girls.\r\n\r\nThere is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claim them. Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is needed and maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They have worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage House which doubles as classroom spaces.   Over the years this school has become more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent slums.  Today, 300 students representing multiple grade levels up to 7th standard attend this school,  all crammed in a space not more than 2000 square feet.  When the school day is over the space reverts to being the living quarters for the 30  resident orphans and their caretakers.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7229-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-461\" alt=\"DSCF7229 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7229-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees ($ 7)  per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable to their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the Sahar slum kids would receive no education.\r\n\r\nAt the Merces - Giriz orphanages the girls attend  schools in the local community.  They all take a bus or walk to get to school.   Their school fees are borne by the HMBT along with any contribution given by family members of the orphans.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-617\" alt=\"DSC01053 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-04-11 12:58:41','2014-04-11 12:58:41','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(808,1,'2014-04-11 13:01:48','2014-04-11 13:01:48','There are three main orphanage sites run by the HBT:   Sahar Slum Orhanage,  Merces Orphanage,  and Giriz Orphanage\r\n\r\n<strong>Sahar Slum Orphanage:</strong>\r\n\r\nThis ophanage is located in a Mumbai slum called Sahar Village and is adjacent to the International Airport in Mumbai (<a title=\"Postal Addresses\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/contact/postal-addresses\">see location</a>).  There are 30 resident orphans living here and their care taker known as <a title=\"Amma\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/history/sister-bios/amma\">Amma</a>.    On most days Sisters of the HMBT are also there.   The orphanage house is also used as a school that serves 300 children from the surrounding slums.  At the end of the school day the space reverts back to being an orphanage.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01160-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-593\" alt=\"DSC01160 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01160-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"427\" /></a>             <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7475-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSCF7475 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7475-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Merces Orphanage:</strong>\r\n\r\nThis is the largest orphanage.  It is located just north of the city of Mumbai near a suburb called Vasai (<a title=\"Postal Addresses\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/contact/postal-addresses#vasai\">see location</a>).  Approximately 100 orphans live in this house which is only about 2000 square feet.  It is also the primary residential quarters of Srs. Paulette and Eliza and two other sisters.  It is a very busy and congested house but is kept well organized.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01034-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-599\" alt=\"DSC01034 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01034-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>      <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01022-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-600\" alt=\"DSC01022 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01022-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Giriz Orphanage:    </strong>\r\n\r\nThis orphanage is located about 2 Km. from the Merces Orphanage (<a title=\"Postal Addresses\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/contact/postal-addresses#vasai\">see location</a>).   It is the newest building of the three,  and is currently used to house the older,  most independent girls under the supervision of the Handmaids.  Currently about 7-10 girls reside here.   Here they have a chance to focus on their school studies  in a more quiet environment.   Across the road from this orphanage is the Giriz Formation House of the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity Order.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01190-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-608\" alt=\"DSC01190 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01190-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Orphanages','','inherit','open','open','','222-revision-v1','','','2014-04-11 13:01:48','2014-04-11 13:01:48','',222,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/222-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(809,1,'2014-04-11 13:02:25','2014-04-11 13:02:25','There are three main orphanage sites run by the HBT:   Sahar Slum Orhanage,  Merces Orphanage,  and Giriz Orphanage\r\n\r\n<strong>Sahar Slum Orphanage:</strong>\r\n\r\nThis ophanage is located in a Mumbai slum called Sahar Village and is adjacent to the Internationa