 Orphanages</strong></span>:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity Orphanage,  Sapodi Wadi,  Kawlar Budruk,  Mari Naka,  <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Merces</span>,  Vasai,  District Thane   401 201,   Mumbai,    India</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&amp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity Orphanage,  Chauri Wadi,  Giriz Talaw,  <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Giriz</span>, Vasai,  District Thane   401 201,  Mumbai,  India</p>\r\n[googlemap height=\"300\" zoom=\"12\" lat=\"19.3599382\" long=\"72.7892803\"][marker lat=\"19.3599382\" long=\"72.7892803\" title=\"Merces Orphanage\"][marker lat=\"19.3715985\" long=\"72.7951597\" title=\"Giriz Orphanage\"][/googlemap]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Postal Addresses','','inherit','open','open','','481-revision-v1','','','2014-04-11 13:06:28','2014-04-11 13:06:28','',481,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/481-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(812,1,'2014-04-11 13:07:09','2014-04-11 13:07:09','<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span id=\"sahar\" style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Sahar Slum Orphanage &amp; School</strong></span>:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity Orphanage, Rd. No. 2, Church Pakadi, <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Sahar Village</span>, Andheri  East,  Mumbai  400099, India</p>\r\n[googlemap height=\"300\" zoom=\"12\" lat=\"19.1017135,72.8681533\"][marker lat=\"19.1017135,72.8681533\" title=\"Sahar Orphanage\"][/googlemap]\r\n\r\n[anchor name = vasai]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span id=\"vasai\" style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong> Merces  &amp; Giriz  Orphanages</strong></span>:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity Orphanage,  Sapodi Wadi,  Kawlar Budruk,  Mari Naka,  <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Merces</span>,  Vasai,  District Thane   401 201,   Mumbai,    India</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&amp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity Orphanage,  Chauri Wadi,  Giriz Talaw,  <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Giriz</span>, Vasai,  District Thane   401 201,  Mumbai,  India</p>\r\n[googlemap height=\"300\" zoom=\"12\" lat=\"19.3599382\" long=\"72.7892803\"][marker lat=\"19.3599382\" long=\"72.7892803\" title=\"Merces Orphanage\"][marker lat=\"19.3715985\" long=\"72.7951597\" title=\"Giriz Orphanage\"][/googlemap]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Postal Addresses','','inherit','open','open','','481-revision-v1','','','2014-04-11 13:07:09','2014-04-11 13:07:09','',481,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/481-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(813,1,'2014-04-11 13:11:05','2014-04-11 13:11:05','There are three main orphanage sites run by the HBT:   Sahar Slum Orhanage,  Merces Orphanage,  and Giriz Orphanage\r\n\r\n<strong>Sahar Slum Orphanage:</strong>\r\n\r\nThis ophanage is located in a Mumbai slum called Sahar Village and is adjacent to the International Airport in Mumbai (<a title=\"Postal Addresses\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/contact/postal-addresses\" target=\"_blank\">see location</a>).  There are 30 resident orphans living here and their care taker known as <a title=\"Amma\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/history/sister-bios/amma\">Amma</a>.    On most days Sisters of the HBT are also there.   The orphanage house is also used as a school that serves 300 children from the surrounding slums.  At the end of the school day the space reverts back to being an orphanage.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01160-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-593\" alt=\"DSC01160 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01160-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"427\" /></a>             <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7475-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSCF7475 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7475-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Merces Orphanage:</strong>\r\n\r\nThis is the largest orphanage.  It is located just north of the city of Mumbai near a suburb called Vasai (<a title=\"Postal Addresses\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/contact/postal-addresses#vasai\" target=\"_blank\">see location</a>).  Approximately 100 orphans live in this house which is only about 2000 square feet.  It is also the primary residential quarters of Srs. Paulette and Eliza and two other sisters.  It is a very busy and congested house but is kept well organized.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01034-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-599\" alt=\"DSC01034 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01034-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>      <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01022-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-600\" alt=\"DSC01022 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01022-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Giriz Orphanage:    </strong>\r\n\r\nThis orphanage is located about 2 Km. from the Merces Orphanage (<a title=\"Postal Addresses\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/contact/postal-addresses#vasai\" target=\"_blank\">see location</a>).   It is the newest building of the three,  and is currently used to house the older,  most independent girls under the supervision of the Handmaids.  Currently about 7-10 girls reside here.   Here they have a chance to focus on their school studies  in a more quiet environment.   Across the road from this orphanage is the Giriz Formation House of the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity Order.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01190-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-608\" alt=\"DSC01190 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01190-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Orphanages','','inherit','open','open','','222-revision-v1','','','2014-04-11 13:11:05','2014-04-11 13:11:05','',222,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/222-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(814,1,'2014-04-11 13:13:36','2014-04-11 13:13:36','<strong>Sahar Slums School:</strong>\r\n\r\n[right][carousel name=\"school\"][/right]\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They have worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage House which doubles as classroom spaces.\r\n\r\nOver the years this school has become more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent slums.  Today, 300 students representing multiple grade levels up to 7th standard attend this school, all crammed in a space not more than 2000 square feet.  When the school day is over the space reverts to being the living quarters for the 30  resident orphans and their caretakers.\r\n\r\nThe teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees ($ 7) per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option. They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools,  and the nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families. The HBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the Sahar slum kids would receive no education.\r\n\r\n<strong>School for Merces - Giriz Orphans:</strong>\r\n\r\nAt the Merces - Giriz orphanages the girls attend  schools in the local community.  They all take a bus or walk to get to school.   Their school fees are borne by the HMBT along with any contribution given by family members of the orphans.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-617\" alt=\"DSC01053 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>','School','','inherit','open','open','','381-revision-v1','','','2014-04-11 13:13:36','2014-04-11 13:13:36','',381,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/381-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(815,1,'2014-04-11 13:14:00','2014-04-11 13:14:00','<strong>Sahar Slums School:</strong>\r\n\r\n[right][carousel name=\"school\"][/right]\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They have worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage House which doubles as classroom spaces.\r\n\r\nOver the years this school has become more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent slums.  Today, 300 students representing multiple grade levels up to 7th standard attend this school, all crammed in a space not more than 2000 square feet.  When the school day is over the space reverts to being the living quarters for the 30  resident orphans and their caretakers.\r\n\r\nThe teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees ($ 7) per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option. They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools,  and the nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families. The HBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the Sahar slum kids would receive no education.\r\n\r\n<strong>School for Merces - Giriz Orphans:</strong>\r\n\r\nAt the Merces - Giriz orphanages the girls attend  schools in the local community.  They all take a bus or walk to get to school.   Their school fees are borne by the HBT along with any contribution given by family members of the orphans.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-617\" alt=\"DSC01053 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01053-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>','School','','inherit','open','open','','381-revision-v1','','','2014-04-11 13:14:00','2014-04-11 13:14:00','',381,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/381-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(816,1,'2014-04-11 13:17:54','2014-04-11 13:17:54','This page will profile recently funded projects.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed October 2013</span>:    The rusting and broken down stairs at the Merces Orphanage house needed replacement.  It was the main passage way for 100 orphans to get to their upstairs living quarters.  The cost of this project was 232,500 Rupees (aproximately $ 4,850).   This entire project was funded by a single benefactor who wishes to remain anonymous.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01021-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSC01021 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01021-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed late 2012</span>:   Power outages at the Merces Orphanage are frequent, almost daily for brief periods of time.   During this time a back-up electric battery system was needed to power several light bulbs.  The cost of this project was 52,000 Rupees (approximately $ 1100).   This entire project was funded by a single benefactor who wishes to remain anonymous.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Invertor-cropped.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-767\" alt=\"Invertor cropped\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Invertor-cropped.jpg\" width=\"550\" height=\"393\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed Fall 2011</span>:   Water used for personal hygeine and washing clothes at the Merces Orphanage house was not sanitary;  it was also uncomfortably cold for bathing.  The reasons of this are described in this section of the Diary of a Visit narrative.  The solution involved sealing the supply well,  then filtering and pumping contaminated well water to a solar heated water tank installed on the roof of the orphanage house.  From here the water is gravity delivered to the first floor.  Not only is the water clean and safe but also warm for bathing in the winter months.  The cost of this project was 200,000 Rupees (approx. $ 4900).   The funds for this project were raised from many individual donors including the congregation of the Zen Buddhist Temple of Ann Arbor, Michigan.\r\n\r\n<a style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01049-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-743\" alt=\"DSC01049 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01049-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>  <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Solar-Water-Tank.jpg\"><img alt=\"Solar Water Tank\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Solar-Water-Tank.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Recently Funded','','inherit','open','open','','509-revision-v1','','','2014-04-11 13:17:54','2014-04-11 13:17:54','',509,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/509-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(817,1,'2014-04-11 13:19:04','2014-04-11 13:19:04','This is a blog of a visit to the HMBT orphanages in December, 2009 written by a 13 year old girl Abby Shah and her father Jayesh Shah.\r\n\r\n[sectiontitle]Sunday, November 22, 2009[/sectiontitle]\r\n\r\n<strong>Planning our trip to India</strong>\r\n\r\nWe\'re planning our trip to India. We are planning to volunteer at the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity orphanage, in the Sahar Slum of Mumbai, where we will be trying to teach the kids there English. We are learning a little bit of Hindi before we go so it will be easier to get to know the people at the orphanage. There will be thirty kids there ages running from 4 to 12.\r\n\r\n[sectiontitle]Wednesday, December 9, 2009[/sectiontitle]\r\n\r\nWe are already starting to get some donations for the Orphanages. This is really exciting we are looking forward to actually meeting the orphans.\r\n<div>\r\n<div>[sectiontitle]Sunday, December 13, 2009[/sectiontitle]</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7035-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-442\" alt=\"DSCF7035 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7035-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>On our first day at the Sahar Orphanage we were welcomed very warmly. The kids knew that we were coming and happy to finally see us. We’ve gone to two of the orphanages so far. At the first one we helped the kids a little with their English writing letters and numbers. At the big orphanage my dad (who is a doctor) checked over the kids and helped diagnose their conditions. I think the kids have a lot of responsibility and they are all mothering each other because they are all like a big family. The sisters devoted their whole lives to help these children and they are doing a really good j0b. It seems like the community the big orphanage is in is really nice, they contribute food on holidays and Sundays. The slums in real life are exactly what they look like in “Slumdog Millionaire”. It’s sad looking at the kids running through the traffic begging for food and money…</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n[sectiontitle]Monday, December 14, 2009[/sectiontitle]\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary2.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary2\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary2-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-372c-849e-1281-fb95cd743eac\">The Sisters running the Sahar Slum Orphanage also run another orphanage at Vasai. There are 200 kids here, boys and girls, aged from 5 to 14. This orphanage is in a country setting.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Yesterday when we were at the Vasai orphanage we saw a girl with polio. Her aged face was the only reason we could tell she was older than 11. She was all curled up and her back was very deformed.  She got polio when she was really young and she survived.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7160-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-446\" alt=\"DSCF7160 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7160-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Her parents couldn’t deal with a crippled child so they abandoned her to the orphanage. The nuns don’t have enough money to buy her a wheelchair or time to do physical therapy. We are using some of the money we collected from donations to get a wheelchair for her so she doesn’t have to ever drag herself around with only her arms again.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary3.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary3\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary3-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-2eb0e328-372f-7b9f-d3da-cb51a7367ade\">Though the traffic is CRAZY here, i think it is safe because everybody is watching out for themselves and looking more at their surroundings. In America there are so many rules that if somebody breaks one, people aren’t prepared and there is panic and confusion.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">People in India seem very casual and easy going. We were walking through the slums to get to the orphanage and we came across a few boys playing outside with a top. They said “hi” and I stopped to watch them and take their picture. They didn’t speak English but they all lined up for me to take a photo.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary4.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary4\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary4-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was surprising that people living in such poverty could be so free and friendly.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Even the dogs seem laid back; they never bark or chase you.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7095-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-443\" alt=\"DSCF7095 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7095-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The slums are very smelly and dirty. There are open sewers and piles of garbage throughout the slum village. The filth is scattered around houses and the marketplace.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary5.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary5\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary5-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">And yet there is still beauty in the slums…</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7227-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-471\" alt=\"DSCF7227 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7227-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"427\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">We have been visiting the Sahar slum orphanage that is run by sisters Eliza and Paulette of the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity. Today we went to the orphanage just expecting the thirty orphans but we found out that the orphanage is also the site of a low cost school for the slums. There were 500 kids aged 3-14 packed into classrooms with a collective space similar to a three bedroom apartment.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary7.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary7\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary7-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3731-87c0-c81e-8d26bdc27188\">Some kids start school late so there are a few older kids in lower standards (grades). For example there is a girl in this slum school who was born and raised in a small village and her family just moved to the slum area to get jobs in the city. They then started sending her to the school so now she is in the second standard even though she’s already 13 years old.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary8.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary8\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary8-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>          <a style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary9.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary9\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary9-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">[sectiontitle]Wednesday, December 16, 2009[/sectiontitle]</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">We were waiting outside the Sahar Orphanage and I was sketching out possible pictures for the kids to learn how to draw. A group of 4th standard slum kids just getting out of school walked by in their uniforms. They stopped to look at my pictures and my dad sat them all down around me and handed out sheets of paper. A boy and a small girl got their pencils out and I taught them how to draw a dinosaur. It was a happy experience changing this group of slum kid’s day from just average to great. They really like getting one on one attention and it feels really good to help these kids.</p>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary10.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary10\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary10-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\nOn the same day we did a friendship bracelet project with the orphans. Some of the kids caught on really fast and didn’t need any help; they helped some of the younger kids who didn’t understand how to make the bracelets.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary12.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary12\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary12-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\nTalking with Sister Eliza, we learned more about the history of the orpahange. An old couple lived in a shack, in the Sahar Village slums, just behind the Oberoi Flight Kitchen. The husband worked pumping water from the nearby well. He was somehow murdered on the Flight Kitchen’s property and his body was thrown in a well. The Kitchen compensated the wife by giving her property on which she then built a small slum house. When she died she left the house and property to the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity. Eventually this property was expanded to become what is now the Sahar Village school and orphanage.\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3734-8fa5-fcd9-014bbaa5d876\">Sister Eliza is about 50 years old but she looks like and has the energy of a much younger person. She came from Goa, India. When she was in college in Mumbai she studied Social Work in the slums and that is how she met Sister Paulette. Together they lived in the slums and were homeless until they were left a small home for their work.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sister Eliza is very lively but at the same time very strict with the orphans. All the kids respect her. She is always smiling and seems very happy about her work. She stays busy all day long. In the morning she teaches 4th standard at the orphanage/school. In the afternoon she goes and teaches at a private school to earn money for the orphanage. Every Saturday night she leaves for Vasai to join Sister Paulette for the weekend. Between teaching, traveling back and forth between her three orphanages, and running the orphanages, she’s left with no time to herself.</p>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary13.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary13\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary13-225x300.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n\r\nSister Paulette worked with Mother Teresa for about twenty years until she became very sick and was sent to a hospital in Mumbai. She was paralyzed and the doctor told her she was going to be bedridden for life. Sister Paulette told us that Mother Mary appeared to her and told her to get up and go back to help people. Somehow she had a miraculous recovery and started working in the Sahar Village Slum. Today she spends most of her time at the Vasai Orphanage helping the 200 kids there. Sister Paulette told us that she believes in “fighting poverty by education”. She says: “Giving food helps for a day or two but educating saves an entire life.”\r\n\r\nAma is the caretaker of the Sahar Orphanage, she monitors the kids and she is like their mother. She gave up her own home and all personal belongings to come and live at the orphanage. She bathes the kids and feeds them and dresses them. She is always there for them and most of the village knows her. Her being there takes a lot of the burden off Sister Eliza and frees her up to be able to go to the other orphanages. Ama can be very strict at times, and she really knows how to keep the kids in order. They are her whole life and she loves them like they are her own children.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary14.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary14\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary14-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe daily schedule for the Sahar Orphanage children starts in the morning with Ama bathing them and then feeding them. For breakfast they get one banana, one glass of milk, bread, butter, and jam. The bread, butter, and jam are donated by the Oberoi Flight Kitchen. Sister Eliza pays three Rupees for each kid to have an egg every morning.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary15.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary15\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary15-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\nAfter breakfast they go to their classrooms until 1:00 p.m.  Ama then feeds them a lunch of dhal, rice, and water. After they eat, they get rest and play time. A tutor comes in the afternoon and works with them. After this they get a snack and have free time until Ama is ready to feed them dinner. Dinner consists of a glass of water, rice, and leftovers from lunch and breakfast.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary16.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary16\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary16-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\nIn Mumbai kids are usually orphaned because either the parents are in jail, they’ve died, or the fathers left the mothers. Often the story is that one or both of the parents have died of AIDS. In cases where the father has left the mother, the mother is often left homeless or unable to cope with a full time job and care for a child.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7598-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-453\" alt=\"DSCF7598 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7598-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nOnce, we were walking home from a restaurant and we passed a frail middle aged woman holding a baby. She looked really sad. She was so desperate that she wasn’t begging for money, she was just standing in the middle of a street saying “khana” (food) to all passers. When we saw her, we gave her a bag of food that we got from the restaurant and she said: “God bless you.” Seeing people like that makes you want to give them everything you have because you know that they need it a lot more than you do.\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary18.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary18\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary18-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3736-a7ee-8ff2-f70c3021eef4\">Poverty in India is EVERYWHERE. You could be inside the property of a five star, top line, hotel but as soon as you walk outside you would see a family bundled up on a few scraps of blankets. Or a mother trying to bathe her children in water from a pipe leak.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary19.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary19\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary19-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3736-fb97-ecd7-dd6ff730c291\">In America poor people on the streets are usually not literally “on the streets.” There are soup kitchens and food lines they can go to, there are people who set up organizations to shelter the homeless for a night or two.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">And if a homeless person wanted to get off the streets, he/she probably could. In India, we did not see soup kitchens or “shelter for the poor” organizations; people are pretty much on their own. There are whole families living under a lean-to they’ve set up with scraps of blankets and wood. We saw a family</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3737-1e3a-f7ca-68ab726c3003\">bathing in water from a sewage leak right on a busy traffic road, and cooking in a tin can over a small fire. These families don’t have enough money to send their kids to school, and they’re too busy trying to get food to even think about education.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">[sectiontitle]Thursday, December 17, 2009[/sectiontitle]</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary20.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-92 alignnone\" alt=\"diary20\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary20-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be1e-85b8-0f6e-6c08da776bc0\">At the Vasai Orphanage we saw that almost every kid had a skin infection on their legs and arms and other parts of the body. My dad sent pictures to an infection specialist at the University of Michigan and he wrote back with helpful advice to have one child with the infection tested at a local hospital.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Yesterday we took an orphan to Holy Spirit Hospital in Mumbai hoping to get some tests done. The hospitals in India are very different from American hospitals. There was a huge line of about forty people all waiting to get their papers and to get checked by just one doctor. When we finally got to see the doctor, he told us what we already thought- the orphan had scabies and bacteria infections of the skin. He did not allow any tests to be done.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">My dad became friends with a pharmacist nearby where we were staying. When the pharmacist heard what we were doing he said that he would give us medicine at the best price he could. We purchased enough medicine to treat all the orphans at both Vasai and Sahar.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7056-cropped-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-448\" alt=\"DSCF7056 cropped (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7056-cropped-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"429\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">We spent a lot of time making charts of which children should take what doses of each medicine. On the last day, my dad weighed all the kids at the Sahar orphanage to make it easier for Sister Eliza to distribute the medication.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7662-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-475\" alt=\"DSCF7662 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7662-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>           <a style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary21.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-93\" alt=\"diary21\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary21-225x300.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be1f-4aba-c7c3-ce380f6890fd\">[anchor name = \"this section\"]At Vasai all the orphans and caretakers bathe with water from a very shallow well. The well is covered by a wire dome. Sister Eliza told us that the kids sometimes misbehaved and threw toothbrushes and spit in the well. Sometimes they even urinated in the well. The kids don\'t have parents to discipline them and Sisters Eliza and Paulette are doing the best they can. The well is also located a few feet away from the pit toilets and we are worried that when it rains there is cross-contamination.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">We talked to the Sisters about our concerns with the current water situation and they said that they were uncomfortable with it also. They have paid a man to go down and clean out the well and they put a solid cover over the well. They also built a locked fence around the well so no kids can get through.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Although this is a good short term solution to the water problem, in monsoon season, there is going to be a lot of cross contamination and the water will become filthy again. . They have been thinking about it for a while and they both thought that the best idea would be to get a solar powered water boiler installed. Getting and installing this boiler will cost 150,000 rupees (the equivalent of a little over 3,000 U.S. dollars). Our short term goal is to raise enough money to buy this boiler for the orphanage.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be20-2889-abfd-6562625193b9\">Today is our last day in Mumbai. We are taking a train to Vadodara to visit my dad\'s family. We are very glad to have had the chance to work at these orphanages.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary23.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-95\" alt=\"diary23\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary23-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be20-7c6d-80ed-f258b5054a58\">At times working at the orphanages was REALLY frustrating. The Orphans would start fighting for attention while we were talking to other kids and grabbing things from other kid’s hands. But at the end of every day at the orphanage, when they were all waving bye to us and walking us to the door shouting “good-bye Dee-Dee” (goodbye big sister) I felt good because I knew that the orphans were really happy. Seeing new people who wanted to help them was a big treat for them.  I was glad that I wasn’t just out seeing the Taj-ma-hal or some other attraction; instead, I was finally doing something that helped someone else.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary24.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-96\" alt=\"diary24\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary24-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Writing this blog has been hard work because we are always doing it at the end of the day when we are exhausted and jet-lagged. I just want to go to sleep but my dad drags me down to the hotel lobby and asks to use the manager’s computer for a while. We go through all the pictures from the day, select the few we actually want to keep, and match them with things that had happened that day.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">After volunteering only for one week I have become amazed that the Sisters have devoted their whole lives to doing this work. It’s REALLY HARD. They have given up everything in their lives to help the orphans and their whole lives revolve around them. The only reason they do ANYTHING is for the orphans. They are so self-less and devoted, and not many people are like them.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7235-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-479\" alt=\"DSCF7235 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7235-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Although this blog is for memories and for showing others how different lives are in the slums in India, it is also to raise money. The Sisters have a wish-list of things they can’t afford. The solar-water boiler for the Vasai orphanage is something we’ve seen that they really need and there is NO way that they are going to get this without donors. Our goal is to raise $3500 for this project. If you are reading this please consider making a donation.</p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div></div>','Diary of a Visit','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision-v1','','','2014-04-11 13:19:04','2014-04-11 13:19:04','',9,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/9-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(818,1,'2014-04-11 13:21:59','2014-04-11 13:21:59','This page will profile recently funded projects.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed October 2013</span>:    The rusting and broken down stairs at the Merces Orphanage house needed replacement.  It was the main passage way for 100 orphans to get to their upstairs living quarters.  The cost of this project was 232,500 Rupees (aproximately $ 4,850).   This entire project was funded by a single benefactor who wishes to remain anonymous.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01021-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSC01021 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01021-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed late 2012</span>:   Power outages at the Merces Orphanage are frequent, almost daily for brief periods of time.   During this time a back-up electric battery system was needed to power several light bulbs.  The cost of this project was 52,000 Rupees (approximately $ 1100).   This entire project was funded by a single benefactor who wishes to remain anonymous.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Invertor-cropped.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-767\" alt=\"Invertor cropped\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Invertor-cropped.jpg\" width=\"550\" height=\"393\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Completed Fall 2011</span>:   Water used for personal hygeine and washing clothes at the Merces Orphanage house was not sanitary;  it was also uncomfortably cold for bathing.  The reasons of this are described in <a title=\"Diary of a Visit\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/diary-of-a-visit#this section\" target=\"_blank\">this section</a> of the Diary of a Visit narrative.  The solution involved sealing the supply well,  then filtering and pumping contaminated well water to a solar heated water tank installed on the roof of the orphanage house.  From here the water is gravity delivered to the first floor.  Not only is the water clean and safe but also warm for bathing in the winter months.  The cost of this project was 200,000 Rupees (approx. $ 4900).   The funds for this project were raised from many individual donors including the congregation of the Zen Buddhist Temple of Ann Arbor, Michigan.\r\n\r\n<a style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\" href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01049-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-743\" alt=\"DSC01049 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01049-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>  <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Solar-Water-Tank.jpg\"><img alt=\"Solar Water Tank\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Solar-Water-Tank.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Recently Funded','','inherit','open','open','','509-revision-v1','','','2014-04-11 13:21:59','2014-04-11 13:21:59','',509,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/509-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(819,1,'2014-04-11 13:23:36','2014-04-11 13:23:36','The left side bar of this page will take you to some typical orphan profiles.\r\n\r\nThere are about 30 orphans at Sahar and about 100 at Merces-Giriz.  They range from 3 years to 16 years old.  Their parents have died either due to disease, violent crime,  self neglect,  or are in prison.\r\n\r\nSome of the kids are not \"orphans\" but have been brought by a parent or family member because they are physically or financially unable to care for them.  Often, there will be one surviving parent or a distant relative that continues to visit their child at the orphanages and this individual will eventually accept the child back.   But while they are there, the HBT Sisters care for them completely.\r\n\r\nOn a typical day they will arise at 5:30-6:00 am.  After eating breakfast they will get dressed and ready for school which  goes till the early afternoon Monday thru Saturday.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01209-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-646\" alt=\"DSC01209 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01209-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"427\" /></a>\r\n\r\nAt Sahar the school is within the orphanage house itself;  at Merces-Giriz the kids take a bus or walk to nearby independent schools.   In the mid-afternoon there is additonal tutoring by a paid teacher at Sahar and by volunteer local college students at Merces-Giriz.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01175-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-645\" alt=\"DSC01175 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01175-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nIn the late afternoon the kids all do homework,  <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01029-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-643\" alt=\"DSC01029 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01029-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nchores,   <a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01027-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-642\" alt=\"DSC01027 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01027-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nthen have play time, take baths, eat dinner and have prayer time.  They typically go to bed around 9 pm.    On Sundays, there is extra time for watching T.V.,  having a party, music, dance,\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01054-Mobile.jpg\"><img alt=\"DSC01054 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01054-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n\r\nand also visits by family members or persons from the community.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Orphan Profiles','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-v1','','','2014-04-11 13:23:36','2014-04-11 13:23:36','',151,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/151-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(821,1,'2014-04-11 13:26:24','2014-04-11 13:26:24','<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01040-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-691\" alt=\"DSC01040 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01040-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"427\" /></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Supriya is currently in 6th standard and has lived at the Merces Orphanage since 2007.   When both her parents died of tuberculosis she was brought to the orphanage by her grandmother who  had to go to work and had no means to support her.   She is expected to return to her grandmother after 10th grade but she is not sure she wants to go back.   She has one brother who is 14 years old who lives in another orphanage and visits on Sundays.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Supriya attends St. Anthony\'s Convent School where she is average in her class of 80 kids.  She hopes to be an aritist someday.</p>','Supriya Naka','','inherit','open','open','','158-revision-v1','','','2014-04-11 13:26:24','2014-04-11 13:26:24','',158,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/158-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(822,1,'2014-04-11 13:29:55','2014-04-11 13:29:55','<p style=\"text-align: center;\">The text, photos, and general layout themes of this website were created and supplied by  Jayesh Shah.   He is an Emergency Medicine physician living in Ann Arbor,  Michigan,  U.S.A.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">He is the current website administrator and the United States contact for these Orphanges.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01230-Mobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-537\" alt=\"DSC01230 (Mobile)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01230-Mobile.jpg\" width=\"427\" height=\"320\" /></a></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">The coding &amp; programming for  this website was done by the following students at the Eastern Michigan University as a class project:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"> Matthew Juntunen,  Vitaly Peker,  Michael Taulbee,  Lei Qian,  Bhakti Wakchaure</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">The map art on the locations page was done by:   Allison Hoff</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"></p>','About this Website','','inheri